commit_message:
Add passwords information into devstack local.conf

Without these information, to run ./stack.sh after first time
is at risk if wrong passwords are provided.

Change-Id: I863d620741f20c133eefe8cef29041a439d68918

commit_message:
Import ml2_odl options in opendaylight mechanism driver

ml2_odl group options must be imported before being
used in mechanism driver.

In addition, we update other opendaylight drivers way
of imporing ml2_odl options accordingly.

Change-Id: Ia11201eae7546f15064a4e45ac84226ea64da0fd
Closes-bug: 1516966

Ethan, file requirements.txt contains requirements for main Heat code, i.e. libraries without which Heat can not work.

commit_message:
Move kombu as a test dependency only

oslo.messaging has kombu in its own requirements, so kombu
is not needed in requirements.txt.
Instead it was moved to test-requirements.txt file because
it is explicitly imported for functionnal tests.

Change-Id: I952263f1d2c61a3b700824914da499b1ece91b78

commit_message:
Add liberty release notes in YAML format

This commit takes all the Liberty release notes from the wiki[1] and
moves them into reno YAML files.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ReleaseNotes/Liberty#OpenStack_Identity_.28Keystone.29

Change-Id: I5bb807968f360e31a8fc74e422359a44b5345293

commit_message:
Create default sg rules when create a sg

Sometimes we need to create a default security rule when a new security
group is created. The following patch facilitates the same. The format
of default security group rule is
"ethertype,direction,protocol,port_range_min,port_range_max".
For example:
security_group_default_rules=ipv4:ingress:tcp:22:22,ipv4:ingress:tcp:80:80

Related-bp: create-default-security-rules-when-creating-a-security-group

DocImpact
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I2531506fcd3b31fc2b733ee0cc5c4911a6528e1a

commit_message:
Avoid AttributeError in method _get_callback_info

In method _get_callback_info, we need parameter call is
a bound method, otherwise 'callback.__self__.__class__.__name__'
will raise AttributeError. Use reflection.is_bound_method to
check callback can avoid this.

Change-Id: I7f70ce9a62735139a7310f201154513c5d6075ee

commit_message:
Remove the HP CLIQ proxy driver

This patch removes the deprecated HP Lefthand
CLIQ/SSH based driver.  It also refactors the proxy
class, which was nothing but a wrapper for the 2
drivers.   The LeftHand driver is now entirely based
off of the REST client.

Implements: blueprint deprecate-hp-lefthand-cliq
DocImpact

Change-Id: I12d8bb7b7dcac8ae40796d9d169825265c634a33

commit_message:
Deprecate nova-manage service subcommand

The novaclient already has the following service commands:

service-disable   Disable the service.
service-enable    Enable the service.
service-list      Show a list of all running services.
host-describe     Describe a specific host

This covers what nova-manage service was providing so let's
deprecate the legacy nova-manage subcommand and mark it for
removal in the N release.

UpgradeImpact: nova-manage service is deprecated, use novaclient

Remove 'spec' from profile-update service api

This patch removes the 'spec' parameter from profile_update service API.
We don't allow changes to the spec of an existing profile.

Change-Id: I2f489a44814afe1f9d0bcd0b6500cfe67a59aa90

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-18 01:56:46.000000000', 'message': "Remove spec file profile-update command

We were using profile-update command to create a new profile if 'spec'
is provided. This is an abuse of the command. It is creating confusion
rather than convenience (original thought). This patch removes the
'spec' parameter so users will better understand that 'spec' is designed
to be read-only.

Change-Id: I2ee0aeea2b612dbfb27263dbf2ac203698f257e5
"}]
commit_message:
Remove spec file profile-update command

We were using profile-update command to create a new profile if 'spec'
is provided. This is an abuse of the command. It is creating confusion
rather than convenience (original thought). This patch removes the
'spec' parameter so users will better understand that 'spec' is designed
to be read-only.

Change-Id: I2ee0aeea2b612dbfb27263dbf2ac203698f257e5

commit_message:
Enable initiative action selecting in start_action

This patch adds initiative action selecting support in start_action
method of scheduler module. If no action_id is specified, the first
ready action which is not locked by other worker will be acquired
for running.

Change-Id: Id1f34e3b85148f5d1a67e099f5fcd3fbec406296
Implements: blueprint support-initiative-action-selecting-in-start-action

commit_message:

commit_message:
Prevent Share operations during share migration

Disabled following operations during migration because they are
not supported:
- extend
- shrink
- delete
- create snapshot
- unmanage

This patch also changes task_state field value from MIGRATING to
MIGRATION_IN_PROGRESS, in order to better parse the string to
determine if the share is busy specifically due to migration.

Also made some small adjustments to migration code, such as moving
the action of reverting access rules to status MIGRATION_IN_PROGRESS
instead of MIGRATION_COMPLETING, in order to better fit
the migration statuses for admin diagnosis, future 2-phase
and error cleanup implementations.

Replaced unused ShareIsBusy exception with ShareBusyException that
is thrown on busy task_state statuses.

Closes-Bug: #1513436
Change-Id: I28123fe04b93331d82932051539aba1d9e507f68

commit_message:
Fix exception on uploading a volume to image with glance v2 API

This fixes an exception on uploading a volume to image when
the glance v2 api is enabled. Also, this adds the unit tests
for updating metadata and data both with glance API v1 and v2.

FakeSchema class was backported to stable/kilo too.

Change-Id: Id70eff82837c0af1f033a2bb749ef367cd9e32fb
Closes-bug: #1478737
(cherry picked from commit beef71d0f8edf5770f8fe95d85e5ea230ddd6f10)

[{'created': '2015-10-07 20:53:37.000000000', 'message': "Downstream Fix for Genconfig

This patch adds the opts.py file to the tree as a fix for deployers
that package cinder. The opts.py file is no longer being deleted right
away by generate_sample.sh after the cinder.sample.conf is being
generated.

This patch also introduces a pep8 check to make sure that the opts.py
file is up to date, so that it will catch when new opts get added to
Cinder without the opts.py being updated.

To support the ability to keep and check the opts file a number
of changes were needed in the check_uptodate.sh script as well as
the generate_sample.sh script:
    - check_uptodate now takes --checkopts instead of --checkonly
      When checkopts is used the opts.py file is generated using the
      current code and the generated file is compared to the existing
      file.  The check fails if there are differences.
    - generate_sample now has the --nosamplefile option.
      When this option is used, only the opts.py file is generated.
      The oslo-config-generator code is skipped so no sample file
      is created.
    - generate_sample also has some coding style consistency changes.
    - Added the 'genopts' option to tox so users can generate
      a fresh opts.py without a sample file when necessary.

Closes-Bug: 1501820
Co-Author: Jay Bryant <jsbryant@us.ibm.com>

Change-Id: I1f5494ebb19d5f4e8c651cbeef0acad07ad96829

commit_message:
Downstream Fix for Genconfig

This patch adds the opts.py file to the tree as a fix for deployers
that package cinder. The opts.py file is no longer being deleted right
away by generate_sample.sh after the cinder.sample.conf is being
generated.

This patch also introduces a pep8 check to make sure that the opts.py
file is up to date, so that it will catch when new opts get added to
Cinder without the opts.py being updated.

To support the ability to keep and check the opts file a number
of changes were needed in the check_uptodate.sh script as well as
the generate_sample.sh script:
    - check_uptodate now takes --checkopts instead of --checkonly
      When checkopts is used the opts.py file is generated using the
      current code and the generated file is compared to the existing
      file.  The check fails if there are differences.
    - generate_sample now has the --nosamplefile option.
      When this option is used, only the opts.py file is generated.
      The oslo-config-generator code is skipped so no sample file
      is created.
    - generate_sample also has some coding style consistency changes.
    - Added the 'genopts' option to tox so users can generate
      a fresh opts.py without a sample file when necessary.

Closes-Bug: 1501820
Co-Author: Jay Bryant <jsbryant@us.ibm.com>

Change-Id: I1f5494ebb19d5f4e8c651cbeef0acad07ad96829

commit_message:
Add testcases to check cache invalidation in endpoint filter extension

keystone now has the ability to cache catalog, and will invalidate
the cache when there is any change about the catalog, i.e. add endpoints
to project or remove endpoints from project. But the testcase was missed.

The patch focus on endpoint project association and leave endpoint_group
project association as it is. since these two APIs should impact the
endpoints in theory but it's doesnot in practice. So, add some testcases
to test its impact on catalog is impossible.

There is another bug filed [1] and testcases for endpoint group will be
added when that bug is fixed.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystone/+bug/1516469

Change-Id: Ie85679111e0f8b9d00e11155594db391eb92c09f
Closes-Bug: #1516468

commit_message:
Clarify is_domain project attribute in API version 3.5

The is_domain project attribute is actually visible in the 3.5
version of the API, although it doesn't have any effect until
version 3.6.

[{'created': '2015-11-17 21:39:20.000000000', 'message': "Allow in-place updates for all compatible types

We previously only allowed a resource to update in-place when the 'type'
field in the old and new templates matched. In an age of environment type
mappings, this is incorrect. Instead, allow a resource to be updated
in-place when the old and new resource plugins are of the same class, since
this is actually what determines whether handle_update is capable of
correctly updating the resource in-place.

There is a special-case for TemplateResource as we currently subclass it
for each template type, but all TemplateResource subclasses are in fact
capable of converting between each other via a stack update.

Change-Id: Iba4abf5efd9737ca6a17d8c91d5c54ab6d3f12e0
Co-Authored-By: Zane Bitter <zbitter@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1508115
(cherry picked from commit 98044dbd17c703e6062752f043e1cac6563e3589)
"}]
commit_message:
Allow in-place updates for all compatible types

We previously only allowed a resource to update in-place when the 'type'
field in the old and new templates matched. In an age of environment type
mappings, this is incorrect. Instead, allow a resource to be updated
in-place when the old and new resource plugins are of the same class, since
this is actually what determines whether handle_update is capable of
correctly updating the resource in-place.

There is a special-case for TemplateResource as we currently subclass it
for each template type, but all TemplateResource subclasses are in fact
capable of converting between each other via a stack update.

Change-Id: Iba4abf5efd9737ca6a17d8c91d5c54ab6d3f12e0
Co-Authored-By: Zane Bitter <zbitter@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1508115
(cherry picked from commit 98044dbd17c703e6062752f043e1cac6563e3589)

commit_message:
Removes support for Hyper-V Server 2008 R2

Support for Windows / Hyper-V Server 2008 R2 has been deprecated in
Liberty and it is no longer supported in Mitaka.

Removes the log warning.
Removes the usage of *utils modules using the old WMI namespace
'root/virtualization'.
Removes the CONF.hyperv.force_hyperv_utils_v1 config option.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I1ec83f852d23758bc91da8fd8021b1bed34c63b3
Closes-Bug: #1508066

(3 comments)

TL;DR: I think [1] can simply be reverted.

I don't think this patch is needed. Looking at [1]:

1. Prior to that change, all the following options were allowed: '--router:external=True', '--router:external=False', '--router:external True', '--router:external False' and '--router:external' (which set the value to True). This was because neutronclient ignored unrecognized values (such as 'router:external', which was not defined anywhere) and passed it on to neutron-server (which did recognize it and handled it).

2. The said patch only allowed '--router:external', causing the breakage.

3. This patch doesn't re-allow '--router:external True' and '--router:external False', so the backward compatibility is still broken.

We did check this on an upstream version of neutron-server and an older version of neutronclient. Might be that some changes were made to neutron-server after [1] was merged, which made [1] no longer needed?

[1]: Ibb100d54a5fd8b04ac5e1fc3a26826c695f4d951 (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/96372/)"}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-05-14 11:18:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

John's suggestion seems to be applicable. Backwards compatibility should beat help message completeness, so if there is no way for argparse to document an argument without actually parsing it, then we can revert the orignal patch that broke it. Note that we should reopen the bug for the reverted patch to track it."}, {'account_id': 6579, 'date': '2015-05-17 11:28:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 6579, 'date': '2015-05-17 11:45:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

TL;DR: John and myself found a way to make it work properly and keep the help message, using argparse nargs.

Using the 'nargs' example taken: https://infohost.nmt.edu/tcc/help/pubs/python/web/argparse-add_argument.html

The help message:
  --router:external [{True,False}]
                        Set network as external, it is only available for

The following syntax option will be accepted:
True: '--router:external=True', '--router:external=true', '--router:external True', '--router:external true','--router:external'
False: '--router:external=False', --router:external=false', '--router:external False', '--router:external false', Nothing specified (default)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-17 12:19:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

@Akihiro
Thank you for that review, nargs is definitely too fragile.
Sadly, I currently don't see any way we can make argparse to accept all permutations in parallel.
Specifically, it's not possible for argparse to consider an argument to be equal to a value just by specifying it's name, and in parallel having that very same argument optionally be followed by a value.
Meaning, having both:
neutron net-create test_net --router:external
and
neutron net-create test_net --router:external=<True,true,False,false>

Therefore, I think the solution is to revert Ibb100d54a5fd8b04ac5e1fc3a26826c695f4d951"}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-29 06:21:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Nir, I think it's time to propose a revert then."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-06-29 13:02:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I am okay with a revert patch.

Unknown the option mechanism makes it hard to introduce
user-friendly options and help messages even though it is useful for private extensions.

IMHO, we should release the new major version which has no backward-compatibility and the version of neutronclient does not support unknown options and all options should be defined explicitly. It is the way almost all client projects do. Of course, it is a problem for vendor extensions, but we need a more clear way to define such options. At least we should not depend on the unknown option mechanism in the future.'}, {'account_id': 6579, 'date': '2015-06-30 09:48:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-06-30 09:57:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

[{'created': '2015-05-12 14:22:59.000000000', 'message': "networks: allow --router:external=False/True syntax, again

In previous neutronclient versions, we allowed the following syntax to set
network as external: --router:external=False or --router:external=True.

Since Ibb100d54a5fd8b04ac5e1fc3a26826c695f4d951 was merged, this syntax
no longer works.

This case somewhat reminds the issue ihrachys handled with in
Ib374d1cc499e4f1e5242f1b438bc65512c109e40, quote:
Client libraries should be backwards compatible.
The change that introduced the regression cannot be reverted. First,
because it's correct in essence and fixed a valid bug in neutron client
CLI, and second (and more importantly), we don't want to break backwards
compatibility for users that currently use 2.3.5+ version that already
included the new style of the argument.

This fix will re-add the support for the old style for  setting the
--router:external attribute.

same as the other fix mentioned above, since this is ugly we should
hide that mess from users by suppressing help entries for new arguments.

Change-Id: Idbae5461dcaeff3da48d773e323977afcdc6f85e
Closes-Bug: #1451391

"}, {'created': '2015-05-17 11:28:20.000000000', 'message': "Allow --router:external=False/True syntax again

In previous neutronclient versions, we allowed the following syntax to set
network as external: --router:external=False or --router:external=True.

Since Ibb100d54a5fd8b04ac5e1fc3a26826c695f4d951 was merged, this syntax
no longer works.

This case somewhat reminds the issue ihrachys handled with in
Ib374d1cc499e4f1e5242f1b438bc65512c109e40, quote:
Client libraries should be backwards compatible.
The change that introduced the regression cannot be reverted. First,
because it's correct in essence and fixed a valid bug in neutron client
CLI, and second (and more importantly), we don't want to break backwards
compatibility for users that currently use 2.3.5+ version that already
included the new style of the argument.

This fix will re-add the support for the old style for  setting the
--router:external attribute.

Same as the other fix mentioned above, since this is ugly we should
hide that mess from users by suppressing help entries for new arguments.

Change-Id: Idbae5461dcaeff3da48d773e323977afcdc6f85e
Closes-Bug: #1451391

commit_message:
Revert "Add '--router:external' option to 'net-create'"

This reverts commit 096fd1b175085fcc3c46a248b4afb67561fd29ef.

In previous neutronclient versions, we allowed the following syntax to
set network as external: --router:external=False or --router:external=True.
Since Ibb100d54a5fd8b04ac5e1fc3a26826c695f4d951 was merged, this syntax
no longer works.

Conflicts:
	neutronclient/neutron/v2_0/network.py

Change-Id: Idbae5461dcaeff3da48d773e323977afcdc6f85e
Closes-Bug: #1451391

commit_message:
Ensure that stacks can't get stuck IN_PROGRESS

Make sure that any unexpected exceptions are handled by moving the stack to
the FAILED state.

Change-Id: Ic948c2fe5baf23c9c4ced33060f672ca9c278a19
Closes-Bug: #1492433

commit_message:
Update extend_volume API to use versionedobjects

The following patch updates extend_volume API to use
volume versionedobjects.  Changes were made to be
backwards compatible with older RPC clients.  It only
includes changes to the core cinder code.  Changes in
the drivers are left to each driver maintainer to
update.

Note that this patch DOES NOT try to use object dot
notation everywhere, since it would increase the
size of the patch.  Instead, it will be done in
subsequent patches.

Change-Id: I4192b35f8f3e2cd51b94db10b44727f23592ea86
Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-objects

There is an instance delete that fails starting around here when we start tearing down the container:

http://logs.openstack.org/48/219448/3/check/gate-tempest-dsvm-full/672e11a/logs/screen-n-cpu.txt.gz#_2015-09-03_22_07_10_171

2015-09-03 22:07:10.171 DEBUG nova.virt.libvirt.driver [req-32dc93c1-a619-4311-83dd-e347855decd2 tempest-ServersAdminNegativeTestJSON-105603620 tempest-ServersAdminNegativeTestJSON-414787637] [instance: 93dce47b-ad5e-47d8-9c9c-a4047d094f0f] Attempting to teardown container at path /opt/stack/data/nova/instances/93dce47b-ad5e-47d8-9c9c-a4047d094f0f/rootfs with root device: /dev/nbd8 _teardown_container /opt/stack/new/nova/nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py:691
2015-09-03 22:07:10.172 DEBUG nova.virt.disk.api [req-32dc93c1-a619-4311-83dd-e347855decd2 tempest-ServersAdminNegativeTestJSON-105603620 tempest-ServersAdminNegativeTestJSON-414787637] No device found for path: /opt/stack/data/nova/instances/93dce47b-ad5e-47d8-9c9c-a4047d094f0f/rootfs __init__ /opt/stack/new/nova/nova/virt/disk/api.py:311
2015-09-03 22:07:10.172 DEBUG nova.virt.disk.api [req-32dc93c1-a619-4311-83dd-e347855decd2 tempest-ServersAdminNegativeTestJSON-105603620 tempest-ServersAdminNegativeTestJSON-414787637] Release nbd device /dev/nbd8 teardown_container /opt/stack/new/nova/nova/virt/disk/api.py:476
2015-09-03 22:07:10.173 DEBUG oslo_concurrency.processutils [req-32dc93c1-a619-4311-83dd-e347855decd2 tempest-ServersAdminNegativeTestJSON-105603620 tempest-ServersAdminNegativeTestJSON-414787637] Running cmd (subprocess): sudo nova-rootwrap /etc/nova/rootwrap.conf qemu-nbd -d /dev/nbd8 execute /usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/oslo_concurrency/processutils.py:230

It doesn't happen in the disk API, but we do call qemu-nbd -d on the nbd device.

And then the instance file delete fails here:

http://logs.openstack.org/48/219448/3/check/gate-tempest-dsvm-full/672e11a/logs/screen-n-cpu.txt.gz#_2015-09-03_22_07_11_085

I'm wondering if qemu-nbd -d is asynchronous (it probably is, most things in qemu/libvirt are asynchronous).

So we could (1) add some code to see if the nbd device is really freed up after calling qemu-nbd -d, but that might race with another thread spawning an instance that gets that device immediately after it's freed up, or (2) we add some retry logic around the instance file delete code if we get an EBUSY error (with maybe some lsof logging for debug)."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-09-14 14:41:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 17139, 'date': '2015-09-14 15:48:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-14 17:12:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: test nova + lxc using nbd and nova-network

Relies on dca06dc7dec148cac2d9e27cdb20d7d26bb0a941 to enable nbd.

Runs nova with the libvirt + lxc backend.

Doesn't attempt to work with cells or neutron.

Only run tempest smoke tests and tell tempest to not run volume tests.

Depends on a nova change which fixes a weird bug with nova-network that
seems to really hurt the lxc case. Also depends on a debug logging patch
for the container teardown flows.

Depends-On: Ibf5333516a4c5487a3ee7c662e07028789bdd286
Depends-On: Id0cccdb5897a30eacbb3000e3b4a6b93d42e9a1f

Change-Id: I36c9d6d20c7136ba1ea24ee0921db39e74d7f5cc

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: test config for gate-tempest-dsvm-cells-neutron

Copies the same config for gate-tempest-dsvm-cells but uses
neutron instead of nova-network.

1. Has to force tempest to use fixed IP access for ssh tests.
2. Has to disable the vif plugging callback mechanism since cells
   doesn't support the os-server-events API.
3. Uses the same test regex that is in the nova tree.
4. Depends on a devstack change to disable resize tests in Tempest.
5. Depends on a nova change to skip scenario tests that use neutron
   with floating IPs.

Depends-On: I20f46024e45e32c60275703a193a56ae8cfe7eca
Depends-On: Ieb3b117449f56810f1a41fcf43e737ae919b8945

Change-Id: Idb1224da780c0aa8e35cbb80bdf02d44f5030666

commit_message:
Generate Swagger spec from nova api code base

This spec aims to implement auto-generate swagger spec from nova
api code base. This will make the API reference easy to keep
update.

Implements blueprint api-swagger-generate

Change-Id: Ie09f15d37bf512f6479ea7e241de204c50eb051a

One more sample:

Kubernetes also supports swagger and it provides swagger definition via REST API like:

We can get available resources which contains /swaggerapi :

 $ curl http://172.24.4.7:8080
 {
 "paths": [
   "/api",
   "/api/v1",
   "/healthz",
   "/healthz/ping",
   "/logs/",
   "/metrics",
   "/resetMetrics",
   "/swagger-ui/",
   "/swaggerapi/",
   "/ui/",
   "/version"
 ]
 } 
 $

/swaggerapi provides available swagger definitions:

 $ curl http://172.24.4.7:8080/swaggerapi/
 {
 "swaggerVersion": "1.2",
 "apis": [
  {
   "path": "/api/v1",
   "description": "API at /api/v1 version v1"
  },
  {
   "path": "/api",
   "description": "get available API versions"
  },
  {
   "path": "/version",
   "description": "git code version from which this is built"
  }
 ],
 "apiVersion": "",
 "info": {
  "title": "",
  "description": ""
 }
 }

and user can get the detail of each resource by specifying the resource url under /swaggerapi:

 $ curl http://172.24.4.7:8080/swaggerapi/version
 {
 "swaggerVersion": "1.2",
 "apiVersion": "",
 "basePath": "https://10.0.0.5:6443",
 "resourcePath": "/version",
 "apis": [
  {
   "path": "/version",
   "description": "git code version from which this is built",
   "operations": [
    {
     "type": "void",
     "method": "GET",
     "summary": "get the code version",
     "nickname": "getCodeVersion",
     "parameters": [],
     "produces": [
      "application/json"
     ],
     "consumes": [
      "application/json"
     ]
    }
   ]
  }
 ],
 "models": {}
 }'}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2015-11-10 13:18:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
POC: generate swagger spec from api code base

This code just show how to generate swagger from nova code base.(Limited
to only show keypairs api)
There are some extend to existed decorator, schema for including the doc
in the python code.

The doc includes:
* request and response body
* query parameters
* microversion support
* expected errror status code.

More thing need TODO
* action support
* doc the parameter in the url
* reference the api samples

The problem of current nova code base
* The Microversion should declare on the top of method
* The api sample test should enable all the extensions
* We haven't schema and validation for query parameters
* We haven't schema for api response (but tempest have)

generate swagger doc:
    GENERATE_SWAGGER=true tox -e functional test_api_doc

import swagger(nova/doc/source/swagger_specs/swagger_{api_version}.json)
into ui:
    http://editor.swagger.io/#/

Change-Id: Ic53065c4188d1ff3cc503ea1cda6eb23e6f65fe9

commit_message:
Stop using trunk python-troveclient in test runs

Because it has backward incompatible changes like:

I5ab58fd64f4745a2e558392bff649b05401ed57a

So the change here is to use the versions of troveclient
and proboscis from stable/kilo global-requirements.

Change-Id: I4c081e1ffd3ca89f613f952f056e280b909b05ce

This is still role hierarchies, but not called that. Consequently it has some lack of clarity that would be resolved if you simply called this spec Hierarchical Roles. For example, in role hierarchies it is obvious that inheritance is propagated throughout the hierarchy. In your implied/explicit role table it is not. Is inheritance just one level or more than one level? E.g. if role a is explicit and role b is implied, what about role c that is implied from explicit role b. Does a user with explicit role a get role c or not, since b was not explicitly given to the user?
The role hierarchy graph is a directed acyclic graph and not a tree, since it caters for multiple inheritance, so here again there is no difference between the NIST RBAC model and your spec.
Thus I strongly recommend that you change you spec to role hierarchies because I can see nothing in your spec that diverges from the NIST RBAC model.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2014-10-19 21:42:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

1. role ownership
2. role visibility
3. role assignment and enforcement

Do we have to update the policy(.json) files whenever we introduce a new role definition? If so, how?

So I've marked this as a -2 to register the fact that I remain very unconvinced that this is the right approach.  Fundamentally the question this proposal is getting at is where and how we store and process a more complex set of roles. Do we do this by making roles themselves more structured (like proposed here)....or do we do we use the existing mechanisms of inheritance and solve the problem with token bloat. This a hard comparison because the former requires the admin to understand role hierarchies (as well as project hierarchies, assignment inheritance etc.), the later is invisible to them, but we still need to fix it! Will the admin be able to handle the former? I worry about another hierarchy structure an admin must visualise and worry about.....and in the best case just being confused, in the worst case not realising the risk of unintended consequences of something getting a bunch of subordinate roles. I am prepared to have my -2 overruled.....but want us to really understand WHY we are doing this.  Is it just to get round token bloat (if so, is the BEST answer to that problem).  Is it that we really want this model of hierarchy and not the others?  If so, are we going to remove the others or are we just going to make the system yet more complex?"}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2015-04-25 19:58:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

@Henry. There are two separate issues here:

1. How to define more roles with different permissions, in which some of the permissions may be shared between the different roles, and

2. How to support role hierarchies.

In order to solve 1. we do not need role hierarchies. We can simply define more roles and have more complex policies in which permissions are shared between different roles. I don't think any code changes are needed to support this. It does not necessary lead to token bloat, but it will lead to policy bloat as more rules will be needed to assign permissions to roles.

Role hierarchies may make the solution to 1. somewhat simpler, in that users will be able to carry around less roles in their tokens in order to have the full set of permissions. Depending upon how it is implemented, it may or may not make policies simpler. In the current spec it does not make policies simpler as the role hierarchy is not understood by the policy engine. In order to make policies simpler the role hierachy would need to be defined inside the policy itself and the policy engine would be enhanced to understand the hierarchy."}, {'account_id': 11333, 'date': '2015-04-28 18:01:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

I like the idea of not carrying a bloated token around.  However, without a good tool, admins will get confused with either approach.  At the end of the day, it is just implementation detail.

What would help is in separate spec, propose a tool or enhancement to an existing tool which provides the hierarchical view for a role.  We need to help admin get out of the biz of mentally splotting the role hierarchy.  (I can help draft one)  We then keep the ux aspect out this spec.'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-05-05 11:16:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

Implied  Roles

When assigned a role, the user will also
be assigned all roles implied by any prior roles
The hierarchy of the roles will be expanded when
issuing a token.

DocImpact
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: Ibd84f475db464498fa9daed4454fdcd6ccd9c37c

wrong order.

commit_message:
Use keystoneclient.exception directly

keystoneclient.openstack.common.apiclient.exception was import in
ironicclient/shell.py, but it's keystoneclient.exception indeed.
And only ClientException was used.

Meanwhile, apiclient is removed from oslo-incubator, so there is a
potention change in keystoneclient.

So use keystoneclient.exception directly.

Change-Id: I87bab4396996e9b4f7be33643ae49599cb2f2f76

commit_message:
Add python jobs for fuel-web

This is the start of big effort to bring most of Fuel CI
to the OpenStack Infra

At this point we will add just python jobs and make sure that
they work, all jobs are non voting for now because fuel
project strucutre is going to be changed and we don't want
to block with these gates work on project.

Change-Id: I700ba93647018db42d4b4f1acd61333c1397642d

commit_message:
Refactor HP 3PAR share driver to now be HPE

This patch refactors the HP share driver to now be
the HPE share driver.

This is being done because the company responsible for
this driver is now Hewlett Packard Enterprise (HPE).

The driver is now located in the manila/share/drivers/hpe
folder.

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint rebrand-hp-3par-share-driver
Change-Id: I36efc04fa6da088ccb06070d8cd4fe29269cd7ca

I think part of the challenge here is including some of the settings from python side. The way it works right now is pretty convoluted. We have settings stored in conf.js and settings.py and at some point, they are both clobbered into horizon_config which is then made available as hzconfig.

Here's what I think should be the long term goal. First, Move all of the user specific settings like modal_fade, page size, etc.. out of settings and into conf.js. Settings.py should only have settings that an admin can configure. Secondly, conf.js should be a service so that other people can override it with their own settings. But until that is done, we have to find creative ways to make this work....

So for now, my vote would be to build in a default value into toast service itself and use that until we can fix the problem above. Otherwise, its not going to look pretty and will introduce even more things for us to fix down the road. This is something also worth discussion at the summit IMO."}, {'account_id': 9622, 'date': '2015-10-13 21:49:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 26.'}, {'account_id': 9622, 'date': '2015-10-13 22:06:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 26:

Thanks Thai.  

As Thai mentioned, we currently have one settings file, (local_settings.py).  It currently contains Django+Horizon+OpenStack+client-side settings.  This is difficult to understand and not ideal. Since we've been moving toward client-side development, we've come across a need for strictly client-side settings (page size/ toast fade/ future accessibility/ personal customizations etc.). So we should have a separate config file.  This will also resolve the issue of having the framework dependent on openstack_dashboard.

As for backward compatibility, we only have a few to handle."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-13 23:57:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 26: Verified-1

"}, {'created': '2015-09-22 01:11:38.000000000', 'message': "Angular alert service - add auto dismiss

Client-side settings should not be stored in HORIZON_CONFIG
in settings.py. This mixes up frontend and backend settings.
Instead, we should have one settings file for client-side
and one for server-side.

The client-side settings have been moved to
horizon/static/framework/conf/conf.js

This patch auto dismisses 'info' and 'success' messages.

To test:
1. Make sure you copy conf.js.example into your conf.js.
2. Insert 'horizon.framework.widgets.toast.service'
as dependency (for example, into launch-instance-model)
3. Put several toastService.add(<type>, <message>);
and see that they are dismissed.
4. Also, change the auto_fade_alerts setting in conf.js
to see it adjust accordingly.
5. Check that legacy toast messages are dismissed properly too.

Partially Implements: blueprint launch-instance-redesign
Change-Id: I848c8e495f1a360aecc3a7353011b69aaead79e8

commit_message:
Angular alert service - add auto dismiss

This patch auto dismisses 'info' and 'success' messages for
the Angular toast service.  It uses settings defined in
conf.js in the framework directory, which were copied over
from settings.py. We've copied over those settings
because we don't want to mix client-side settings with
other settings.  This is a first step in that goal.

To test:
1. Insert 'horizon.framework.widgets.toast.service'
as dependency (for example, into launch-instance-model.service.js)
3. Put several toastService.add(<type>, <message>);
and see that they are dismissed.
4. Also, change the auto_fade_alerts setting in conf.js
to see it adjust accordingly.

Partially Implements: blueprint launch-instance-redesign
Change-Id: I848c8e495f1a360aecc3a7353011b69aaead79e8

commit_message:
Fix typos for stack.sh and lib of comments and message

Fix 10 comments and 1 message

stack.sh
  Certicate => Certificate (comment)
lib/stack
  Sentinal => Sentinel (comment)
lib/neutron-legacy
  overriden => overridden (comment)
  necesssary => necessary (comment)
  notifiy => notify (message)
  notifations => notifications (comment)
lib/rpc_backend
  orginal => original (comment)
  cofiguration => configuration (comment)
lib/stack
  confgured => configured (comment)
lib/swift
  additinal => additional (comment)
  calclution => calculation (comment)
  maximun => maximum (comment)

Change-Id: I3637388b67decb007cd49af9addecc654009559b

commit_message:
Don't add default route to HA router if there is no gateway ip

When adding an external network with no gateway ip to a HA router,
l3 agent will report exception. The exception comes from the code
of adding default route to HA router. However, if there is no
gateway ip in the external network, there is no need to add such
route.

Change-Id: I41d6a292c903758f408d3d93a64dca7adeeb5769
Closes-Bug: #1515209

commit_message:
Use unit.new_user_ref consistently

Replace all hand created user refs with calls to new_user_ref().

Note: LDAP live testing code will be updated in a follow on patch.
They require more testing before submission.

Change-Id: I73b1d869534ac3a1bcd2404ef1dd3a0d5b7ea518

commit_message:
Reference correct group in haproxy_config.yml

Currently, playbooks/vars/configs/haproxy_config.yml references group
metering-alarm_all, however this group is not defined in
etc/openstack_deploy/env.d.  This commit updates haproxy_config.yml
to use service group aodh_api instead.

Closes-Bug: #1512676

Change-Id: I93ac55edb15130cd1afa069a638f724be91cbe3b
(cherry picked from commit e13a76bb3aa094bfda36740b47f33cb4b722db04)

commit_message:
3PAR Fix find_existing_vluns

When 3PAR iSCSI driver is configured for multipath, with multiple
ip addresses in hp3par_iscsi_ips, find_existing_vluns fails to return
more than 1 vlun.  The problem with this is that every time
initialize_connection is called, the driver will not find the vlun it expects
to be there, and then it will create a new one.

This patch removes the break inside of find_existing_vluns, so that it
returns the entire list, not just the first vlun.

Change-Id: I0861745717cf9045e10a030dc25fab419f7b1f58
Closes-Bug: #1515033

commit_message:
Drop Python 2.6 tests for python-ironicclient

We're about to release a new ironicclient that drops py26 support, but
I'd like to drop the py26 tox env before doing so. This change is
required to do that.

Change-Id: Ic6585041d5842659201154bf3ef76d1c29825047

commit_message:
Add support for IP Version in Horizon FW-Rule

Currently IP Version can be specified during creation/updation
of firewall rules in CLI, but not in Horizon.
This patch adds the support for IP Version in Horizon.

Change-Id: I206c84501248c393167b060e0329dc1b0ea02f14
Closes-Bug: #1503947

commit_message:
Wait until additional window is opened in integration tests

Provide a special predicate for that. This should stabilize tests
involving opening some external links from Horizon.

Implements blueprint: integration-tests-hardening

Change-Id: Icc764273a6fc717a04f31e8e522a6018ac994b0e

commit_message:
Reset stack status even when lock engine_id is None

Having a stack which is wedged UPDATE_IN_PROGRESS due to another bug,
restarting heat-engine should have resulted in the stack being reset to
UPDATE_FAILED. However the reset was skipped because the lock engine_id
was None.

This change removes the engine_id check since it is possible in practice
for an UPDATE_IN_PROGRESS stack to not be locked.

Since it is possible for the stack to change state in the unlocked
window, a check is added that the stack is still IN_PROGRESS before the
reset is performed.

Change-Id: I1739ccbdf75af35aac5be16b99200975df58b8e2
Closes-Bug: #1514615

commit_message:
Fix the wrong method name

The correct method name should be `remove_endpoint_from_project`
according to the definition in the controller layer or the name
of abstract method.

Partial-Bug: 1516468

commit_message:
libvirt: add cpu schedular priority config

Enhances the cputune configuration to make possible to set
a schedular priority.

Blueprint: libvirt-real-time
Change-Id: I2b2cdebb28b2e452d64924e0f5da93b49b2ab6cb

commit_message:
Fix RC CLI to work with Object from Bay changes

Fix RC CLI to work with Object from Bay changes. In the list
API explicitly pass the bay_ident for which the query is
supposed to be made.

Change-Id: I6093b0e062b72471abc32b968076dcec67e6d6dd
Partially-Implements: bp objects-from-bay

commit_message:
Swap Facter[].value with Facter.value()

  This commit swaps out the usage of Facter['operatingsystem'].value
  with Facter.value(:operatingsystem) in all neutron providers that
  use the array method on a ruby module style syntax.

  This commit doesn't actually fix anything that is broken just
  implements a specific syntax to keep consistency across Puppet
  OpenStack modules.

  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/243849
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/243854

Change-Id: I623f92a5071c4e61a614319ece08b9495d83ff59

commit_message:
[install] Fix nova controller install on Debian

This patch fixes numerous issues present in the guide for installing
nova in the controller for Debian:
- Lack of apt-get command
- Edition of nova.conf which isn't needed for things handled by debconf
(like keystone_authtoken, rabbit, and db management).

Change-Id: Id68c2eb489aec1e968047477d8efe53121e81f6f

commit_message:
Allow customization of db sync command line

Add parameter to glance::db::sync class to allow end
users to add command line parameters to the db sync command.

Change-Id: I043dd9560f7d5eb7bc18721e759e5f61186f5cf7
Partial-bug: #1472740

configs in them, like SAIO does.

commit_message:
doc: Update LBaaS v2 setup for Liberty

- Updated LBaaS v2 setup to use Octavia.
- Removed the old cirros image URL, the default should be sufficient.
- Fixed nova boot commands based on Liberty DevStack.
- Added sleeps to LBaaS v2 commands since most commands
  can take a few seconds to complete.
- Added wait to load balancer creation since it can take
  a few minutes to complete.
- Wrapped long lines in the descriptions.

Change-Id: Ib4a3f02ebc2606e3e16591ae3a23676cb0a6cd64

[{'created': '2015-11-05 22:12:15.000000000', 'message': 'OVS agent: handle deleted ports on each rpc_loop iteration

Currently rpc loop processes ports only in case polling is required
(message from ovsdb monitor) or there are port_updated notifications from
server or security group notifications.
In case of just port_deleted notifications port processing is not
triggered during rpc loop.
This may lead to agent accumulating a big amount of deleted ports
and processing all of them at once during next iteration when polling is
required or any notification from server, which might be quite tough for
the agent. Tough means agent will be irresponsive while processing deleted
ports.
The patch makes port deletion processing more gradual.

Closes-Bug: #1491922
Change-Id: I0e1f6dfbf5b56fb18a978d6214e1768560d8ac98
(cherry picked from commit 6d51ef5d2e275d0d260a592d3ab8ed8a76a63421)
'}]
commit_message:
OVS agent: handle deleted ports on each rpc_loop iteration

Currently rpc loop processes ports only in case polling is required
(message from ovsdb monitor) or there are port_updated notifications from
server or security group notifications.
In case of just port_deleted notifications port processing is not
triggered during rpc loop.
This may lead to agent accumulating a big amount of deleted ports
and processing all of them at once during next iteration when polling is
required or any notification from server, which might be quite tough for
the agent. Tough means agent will be irresponsive while processing deleted
ports.
The patch makes port deletion processing more gradual.

Closes-Bug: #1491922
Change-Id: I0e1f6dfbf5b56fb18a978d6214e1768560d8ac98
(cherry picked from commit 6d51ef5d2e275d0d260a592d3ab8ed8a76a63421)

commit_message:
OVS agent: flush firewall rules for all deleted ports at once

In some cases, under high load OVS agent has to delete a big amount of
ports during rpc_loop. remove_devices_filter() does iptables-save/restore
for IPv4 and IPv6 which is 4 system calls. It is very expensive and
inefficient to call it for each port individually.

Conflicts:
	neutron/plugins/openvswitch/agent/ovs_neutron_agent.py

Closes-Bug: #1491922
Change-Id: I4cfb2dfcef5088436c7aaae22c8f66e1ea052311
(cherry picked from commit da81ae88929c389f0ba8660c4c8dfb79eec7c0fd)

commit_message:
Remove excessive fallback iptables ACCEPT rules

The previous code was generating a fallback ACCEPT rule for every
port when there should only be one at the very end. The reason that
this wasn't causing a bug is because we have a duplicate rule remover
that was silently throwing away the extras and it happened to get them
in the right order.

Conflicts:
	neutron/agent/linux/iptables_firewall.py

Closes-Bug: #1502906
Change-Id: I83cf574f93b512be1ccefdc8da63e1783d279233
(cherry picked from commit ea8de8a9dd808b1379060e0ce578b8129f45c3ae)

commit_message:
[WIP] Add Network Availability to Host Mapping API

Adds API's for mapping Neutron networks to hosts for mapping availability
of a particular network on a specific host.

TODO:

- API tests
- More unit tests

Change-Id: Ie510123c65c48431b9037f06ef055533718983bc
Partially-Implements: blueprint routed-networks

commit_message:
Basic Tabs now inherit from a Bootstrap Theme

Tabs were pretty basic.  For the most, tabs were using the standard
styles nicely, except when embedded inside of a modal. There was a
lot of adding padding and removing padding to the tab-content and
modal container.  This has been cleaned up.

Also, the 'asterisk' that is used to show when a tab has required
information for a workflow was changed to an icon font.

Many unused styles were removed from horizon.scss.

Partially-Implements: blueprint horizon-theme-css-reorg
Partially-Implements: blueprint bootstrap-html-standards

Change-Id: I929de0ae31a3c2cca9e332956eed755c4e279f3d

hardcoded on the ubuntu-bootstrap provision script

commit_message:
Get kolla path from settings when provisioning box

The path for the kolla source dir was being
hardcoded on the ubuntu-bootstrap provision script
instead of utilizing the path defined in the
PROVIDER_DEFAULTS settings in the Vagrantfile

Change-Id: I0eb752ecf4db580838687c290ccf36810e8a4ff3

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

- gate-kolla-deploy-images-ubuntu-source http://logs.openstack.org/23/242923/1/check/gate-kolla-deploy-images-ubuntu-source/69b5d65/ : SUCCESS in 19m 49s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-11-09 08:24:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Hello,

You are failing the bashate gate because of spacing. You must have indents or multiple of 4 chars.

I am not a vagrant user myself, so I will let the vagrant guys weigh in here, but I would hate to give up all of the other work that the vagrant scripts provide and split of Ubuntu with no reuse.'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-11-09 08:31:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

several code comments.

In general I am not in support of having multiple vagrant implementations - one is hard enough to maintain.

What is the advantage of having this one-off vagrant implementation?  Simpler to understand for ubuntu-AIO?  The model I'd like to go with is one Vagrant "superfile" which implements ubuntu + Centos + libvirt + virtualbox + AIO + multinode in an easy to configure mechanism.  Would appreciate mandre and pbourke's comments on this change.'}, {'account_id': 19148, 'date': '2015-11-09 13:57:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

I thought about it and I tend to agree overall with the review comments.
Initially I created a separate Vagrantfile since I didn't want to pollute the existing one but the more I think about it the more I see duplication across both Vagrantfiles.

I guess a more detailed installation guide could alleviate the barrier for new-comers instead of maintain two separate files since it is inevitable that the second one would will end up growing just like the first one eventually.

I'll combine both Vagrantfiles and bootstrap scripts together and send for another review when ready.

Thanks for the comments."}, {'account_id': 19148, 'date': '2015-11-09 14:08:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Some questions regarding the change set:

1: Any concerns in mounting the kolla/etc/kolla dir in the operator VM at /etc/kolla? The reason being that I want to keep track of all the changes I make to the build-conf and globals file using the source control tools I have installed on my mac
config.vm.synced_folder "../../../etc/kolla", "/etc/kolla", type: "nfs"

2: Would it be possible to not mount the storage/operator and storage/shared inside the VMs?
If the boxes have a 40+GB disk size is there a reason to not keep the registry storage inside the VM itself?

3: Does Kolla works with Ubuntu Vivid? That would avoid having to update the kernel image on trusty

4: Can Kolla run on Docker 1.9+?'}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-11-09 15:27:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

3. Works fine
4. The limitation for docker is because of the Ansible docker module, until somethign changes in that front, Kolla is capped at 1.8.2 for Docker. We are really waiting on Ansible right now.'}, {'account_id': 13039, 'date': '2015-11-18 01:00:03.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Implemented in I4609d7f577e948b04663901afd0c5d1d154c8ac4'}]

commit_message:
Add support for ubuntu when deploying kolla with Vagrant

Created bootstrap.sh script to provision a Ubuntu base box with all dependencies necessary to run kolla
Install the following dependencies:
-docker 1.8.2
-ansible 1.9.4
-python deps

Also created separate Vagrantfile with only support for AIO deployments, focused on new comers that are not interested in multi node support out of the box

Change-Id: I81fe9f5d7ade54efce3e5152b1b67f5cf2c2996e
Implements: blueprint vagrant-ubuntu-support
Signed-off-by: Diogo Monteiro <diogo.gmt@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Drop root for Magnum

This change ensures commands run in the magnum containers are done as the
'magnum' user rather than root.

Change-Id: I18e2febae98aae6d6fc6c61cc2817442f408cb75
Partially-Implements: blueprint drop-root

commit_message:
Fixes interface_file jinja misconfiguration

The amphora jinja templater renders the interfaces_file option with a string of 'None'.
This causes failures while communicating with the Amphora.

Change-Id: I57b16387cc84b3942f0af5fc92320513baaff76e
Closes-Bug: #1516827

commit_message:
Allow customization of db sync command line

Add parameter to designate::db::sync class to allow end
users to add command line parameters to the db sync command.

Change-Id: Iae224e97d91ee24e0aae1b79330f0906ff516508
Partial-bug: #1472740

commit_message:
Add test coverage for cinder::db::mysql

Currently most of the tests in cinder_db_mysql_spec.rb aren't checking
anything, they're just setting up the params framework. This patch will
add test coverage for mysql.

Change-Id: If10a466821f03ae96e7885840829acd79fc3dcce

commit_message:
Delete $IPV6_PUBLIC_NETWORK_GATEWAY IP during cleanup

So that it does not end up being the IP address that is picked to move
back to $PUBLIC_INTERFACE when we call _move_neutron_address_route

Change-Id: I3d29d4f11feff308f6ad5d950ef004b48ec11b67
Closes-Bug: 1514984

If we enable "router_distributed = True" in neutron.conf. we can create dvr router by default.

Is there some scenario that including dvr and non-dvr router at the same time?


In addition, there were some cases to simulate east-west traffic in test_network_basic_ops.py'}, {'account_id': 7350, 'date': '2015-08-18 16:15:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Why do you need this kwargs added ?

I don't see any test that needs that. I am not saying it's a bad idea, just that you should also provide test(s) that use this new argument."}, {'account_id': 12024, 'date': '2015-08-19 00:23:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

There are a few use cases e.g. we have distributed/non-distributed router. Moreover, different vendor may have their vendor specific attributes for the router. By adding the kwargs, it gives us more flexibility to write scenario test cases.'}, {'account_id': 12024, 'date': '2015-08-19 00:25:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Jessica, the distributed=True in neutron.conf is global default parameter. By adding the kwargs, it gives us more flexibility to test router with different args when writing test cases. Please refer above comment, vendor may have specific router attributes.'}, {'account_id': 14885, 'date': '2015-08-21 10:32:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I do agree with Jordan's comments on this. If a new feature is added, a test using it should be added as well. Otherwise it'll be just unused and added weight."}, {'account_id': 12024, 'date': '2015-08-22 16:09:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Daniel, the salient feature that is using it is distributed router. It is beneficial to add this ability to pass additional argument as the test cases are basically the same, but we need to created different type of routers. It doesn't make sense to write all new codes again."}, {'account_id': 14885, 'date': '2015-08-24 07:20:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Tong my concern on this is as follows. Take as an example a function you're enhancing: _get_routers. You want to further improve its features by adding kwargs to be able to choose either distributed or vendor's features.

What I think it'd be great it's to have it bundled together with some test which makes use of this. It may just be an improvement to an already existing test, too.

Again, as an example, test_network_v6 uses that function to set the network up. Why don't you just add a new test to that class which makes use of that feature? This is just an example and a suggestion but hopefully I've been clear about my point on this ;)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-30 16:48:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add kwargs in scenario manager create_router

Currently we cannot pass extra kwargs in scenario manager.py
_create_router method. Adding kwargs to allow scenario test case
to call create_networks to create router with extra arguments like
distributed, etc.

Closes-Bug: #1465872
Change-Id: I6f166e0b96491cff8b5db8e6d297a9d8ddaad10d

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables
* Remove requirements.txt from deps, as this is
  already added automatically


Change-Id: I7e45a5aba221e9b2204264f5e88b8ef1f6bd04e3

* Replace base64.encodestring() with
  oslo_serialization.base64.encode_as_text() to accept Unicode as

* tests-py3.txt: add cinder.tests.unit.test_zfssa

Change-Id: I29a1a752d4cad5796fba1f21fe88238cb4414717

commit_message:
Port zfssa driver to Python 3

* Replace base64.encodestring() with
  oslo_serialization.base64.encode_as_text() to accept Unicode as
  input (encoded to UTF-8). On Python 3, the function decodes base64
  from ASCII to get Unicode.
* tests-py3.txt: add cinder.tests.unit.test_zfssa

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I29a1a752d4cad5796fba1f21fe88238cb4414717

commit_message:
Support service client unit tests for headers also.

Some APIs like create image, returns only headers with empty response body.
We should have unit tests for those API also which required to add header
support in base service client test class.

This commit support header testing for service client and implement
create image unit tests which only return info in headers.

Change-Id: I9a79f862288e5fa827414ce1f26d80bcca4db687

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-19 16:32:53.000000000', 'message': 'determine tgtd ready status through tgtadm

The intention of the iscsi extension _wait_for_iscsi_daemon function is to wait
till the tgtd process boots completely before running any iscsi commands
through the tgtadm command line utility.  The tgtd process utilises a unix
socket for communication with the user and the _wait_for_iscsi_daemon function
asserts the tgtd process status based on the socket presence.  The socket
name/path to use is not specified by iscsi extension configuration but rather
falls-back to a (system-wide) default value[1].  Since tgtd version 1.0.60,
this path changed from /var/run/tgtd.ipc_abstract_namespace to
/var/run/tgtd/socket[2] and now causes a false-negative while waiting for the
tgtd process to boot[3].

This patch follows implementation suggestion from the bug report[3] to avoid
relying on the socket presence but rather to check the tgtd status by
trying to communicate through the tgtadm tool.

[1]
https://github.com/openstack/ironic-python-agent/blob/
  5bbb9ded082f2cfde5e8877e9f33294eb93a5fb7/
  ironic_python_agent/extensions/iscsi.py#L47
[2]
https://github.com/fujita/tgt/commit/d1aa4dcfd691c9409dbad5db49ce6754ce9c1b5a
[3] https://bugs.launchpad.net/ironic-python-agent/+bug/1505923

Change-Id: If3284e0b441fe6c2da507640c08a4bbefd9dad2b
Closes-Bug: #1505923

iscsi commands through the tgtadm command line utility.  The tgtd
process utilises a unix socket for communication with the user and the
_wait_for_iscsi_daemon function asserts the tgtd process status based
on the socket presence.  The socket name/path to use is not specified
by iscsi extension configuration but rather falls-back to a
(system-wide) default value[1].  Since tgtd version 1.0.60, this path
changed from /var/run/tgtd.ipc_abstract_namespace to
/var/run/tgtd/socket[2] and now causes a false-negative while waiting
for the tgtd process to boot[3].

This patch follows implementation suggestion from the bug report[3] to
avoid relying on the socket presence but rather to check the tgtd
status by trying to communicate through the tgtadm tool.

commit_message:
determine tgtd ready status through tgtadm

The intention of the iscsi extension _wait_for_iscsi_daemon function
is to wait till the tgtd process boots completely before running any
iscsi commands through the tgtadm command line utility.  The tgtd
process utilises a unix socket for communication with the user and the
_wait_for_iscsi_daemon function asserts the tgtd process status based
on the socket presence.  The socket name/path to use is not specified
by iscsi extension configuration but rather falls-back to a
(system-wide) default value[1].  Since tgtd version 1.0.60, this path
changed from /var/run/tgtd.ipc_abstract_namespace to
/var/run/tgtd/socket[2] and now causes a false-negative while waiting
for the tgtd process to boot[3].

This patch follows implementation suggestion from the bug report[3] to
avoid relying on the socket presence but rather to check the tgtd
status by trying to communicate through the tgtadm tool.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/ironic-python-agent/blob/
5bbb9ded082f2cfde5e8877e9f33294eb93a5fb7/
ironic_python_agent/extensions/iscsi.py#L47 [2]
https://github.com/fujita/tgt/commit/
d1aa4dcfd691c9409dbad5db49ce6754ce9c1b5a
[3] https://bugs.launchpad.net/ironic-python-agent/+bug/1505923

Closes-Bug: #1505923
Change-Id: If3284e0b441fe6c2da507640c08a4bbefd9dad2b

log_after defaults to 30 seconds. A log message will be emitted if a

timeout, if set, will cause the method to raise TaskTimeout if it

'}, {'created': '2015-11-17 11:30:19.000000000', 'message': "Robustify locking in MessageHandlingServer

This change formalises locking in MessageHandlingServer, which closes
several bugs:

* It adds locking for internal state when using the blocking executor,
  which closes a number of races.
* It does not hold a lock while executing server functions,
  which removes a potential cause of deadlock if the server does its
  own locking.
* It fixes a regression introduced in change
  gI3cfbe1bf02d451e379b1dcc23dacb0139c03be76. If multiple threads
  called wait() simultaneously, only 1 of them would wait and the
  others would return immediately, despite message handling not having
  completed.  With this change only 1 will call the underlying wait,
  but all will wait on its completion.

Additionally, it introduces some new functionality:

* It allows the user to make calls in any order and it will ensure,
  with locking, that these will be reordered appropriately.
* The caller can pass a `timeout` argument to any server method, which
  will cause it to raise an exception if it waits too long.
* The caller can pass a `log_after` argument to any server method,
  which will cause it to raise a log message if it waits too long. It
  can also be used to disable logging when waiting is intentional.

We remove DummyCondition as it no longer has any users.

This change was originally committed as change
I9d516b208446963dcd80b75e2d5a2cecb1187efa, but was reverted as it
caused a hang in a Nova test. This was caused by the locking behaviour
for handling restarting a previously stopped server. The original
patch caused the state to 'wrap' immediately after the user called
wait(). This caused a hang in tests which redundantly called stop()
and wait() multiple times. This new patch only wraps when the user
calls start() again. Callers who do not restart a server will
therefore not be affected by the wrapping behaviour. Callers who do
restart a server will be no worse than before. We add a deprecation
warning on restart, as this operation is inherently racy with this api
and there is a simple, safe alternative.

This new version has been successfully tested against the unit and
functional tests of nova, cinder, glance, and ceilometer.

Change-Id: Ic79f87e7b069c1f62d6121486fd6cafd732fdde7

commit_message:
Robustify locking in MessageHandlingServer

This change formalises locking in MessageHandlingServer, which closes
several bugs:

* It adds locking for internal state when using the blocking executor,
  which closes a number of races.
* It does not hold a lock while executing server functions,
  which removes a potential cause of deadlock if the server does its
  own locking.
* It fixes a regression introduced in change
  gI3cfbe1bf02d451e379b1dcc23dacb0139c03be76. If multiple threads
  called wait() simultaneously, only 1 of them would wait and the
  others would return immediately, despite message handling not having
  completed.  With this change only 1 will call the underlying wait,
  but all will wait on its completion.

Additionally, it introduces some new functionality:

* It allows the user to make calls in any order and it will ensure,
  with locking, that these will be reordered appropriately.
* The caller can pass a `timeout` argument to any server method, which
  will cause it to raise an exception if it waits too long.
* The caller can pass a `log_after` argument to any server method,
  which will cause it to raise a log message if it waits too long. It
  can also be used to disable logging when waiting is intentional.

We remove DummyCondition as it no longer has any users.

This change was originally committed as change
I9d516b208446963dcd80b75e2d5a2cecb1187efa, but was reverted as it
caused a hang in a Nova test. This was caused by the locking behaviour
for handling restarting a previously stopped server. The original
patch caused the state to 'wrap' immediately after the user called
wait(). This caused a hang in tests which redundantly called stop()
and wait() multiple times. This new patch only wraps when the user
calls start() again. Callers who do not restart a server will
therefore not be affected by the wrapping behaviour. Callers who do
restart a server will be no worse than before. We add a deprecation
warning on restart, as this operation is inherently racy with this api
and there is a simple, safe alternative.

This new version has been successfully tested against the unit and
functional tests of nova, cinder, glance, and ceilometer.

Change-Id: Ic79f87e7b069c1f62d6121486fd6cafd732fdde7

commit_message:
Fix dvr update for subnet attach multi subnets

Fix method dvr_update_router_addvm to notify every
router attached to subnet where the vm will boot
on.

In dvr case, when a subnet only attaches to one router,
the subnet will only have one distributed router interface,
which device_owner is "network:router_interface_distributed".
So in this case, get_ports in this method will only get
one port, and it should be unnecessary to break in for loop.

But when a subnet attaches multiple routers, get_ports in
this method will return all distributed router interfaces
and the routers hold those interfaces should be notified
when an instance booted on the subnet. So it should also
be unnecessary to break in for loop.

Closes-Bug: #1427122
Co-Authored-By: Ryan Moats <rmoats@us.ibm.com>
(cherry picked from commit 24fa37e05544316b58357b753360b147878e5d94)

Conflicts:
	neutron/db/l3_dvrscheduler_db.py
	neutron/tests/unit/scheduler/test_l3_agent_scheduler.py
Change-Id: I3a5808e5b6e8b78abd1a5b924395844507da0764

commit_message:
Cap requests at <2.8.0 since it packages urllib3 1.12

We have a cap set on urllib3 at 1.11 and requests 2.8.0, released on
10/6, packages urllib3 1.12, which introduces a conflict.

So cap requests at 2.8.0 to avoid issues with newer urllib3.

Since python-glanceclient depends on requests this will need to sync to
glanceclient on stable/kilo and then we can do a patch version release
of that library.

Partial-Bug: #1476770

Change-Id: I8ff76853220c10565b06ba74a7c75c5a955e871b

commit_message:
[V3] Make service_client use **kwargs

As we discussed on
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/068864.html
All http POST/PUT methods need to contain **kwargs as their arguments.
This patch makes service_client use **kwargs.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I02242ad94989ae234963014aa58ffe7b3787018d

Adding a function prefix before parenthesis

Add a missing translation _ before parenthesis as it is done in defining
all exception messages.

Change-Id: Id80b4bf083d357d6c99006116e453d8b63fbc876

commit_message:
Validate ethertype for icmp protocols

This patch will add the validation function to make sure security_group
rule is not created when ethertype is IPv4 and protocol is icmpv6.

Closes-Bug: #1505832
Depends-On: Ia1a5342a1d568cb1a015e1b7acecf38b8d1f46e1

Co-Authored By: Matt Dorn <madorn@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I4a15935c564aaa48555ed08f6da51113787ecb73
(cherry picked from commit 7335dbdabe6cd2d558f209b2349491efc376352e)

commit_message:
More graceful ovs-agent restart

When the neutron server is down/busy the agent is not able to get any
port info. After the agent restarts, it will not install any new flow.
Cleaning the existing flows will break all networking until the agent
succeeds to sync with the neturon server.

This patch ensures the agent cleans the stale flows only after it
succeeds to sync with the neturon server.

Change-Id: I763fc06a73b6d2f010da65e74241182636dda44d
Closes-bug: #1515075
(cherry picked from commit 0c8121ee68085d67a7b865b5b25c4b3880defc89)

commit_message:
Fix H404/405 violations for scenario tests

There is a lot of H404/405 violations in Tempest now, and that leads
difficult to migrate the code to tempest-lib or the other projects'
repos. This patch fixes these violations for scenario tests.

Change-Id: Ia2b3cdbd0da49eeb16742c1eed05ea56ca41a8f7

commit_message:
Remove novaclient/neutronclient description

When we implemented scenario tests, we were using novaclient and
the other client for doing that. But now we don't use novaclient/
neutronclient at all.
So this patch removes novaclient/neutronclient description.

Change-Id: Ic6c6d9fa3ce36327f4f06d1a33a291c057a9f5bc

commit_message:
Use Keystone v3 API only

Other than Ironic (pending bug 1494776), switch all other
configuration, cli etc to use only keystone v3 API.

Depends-On: I6b3a505936f04d41df18c9599ca3c0b2ffd26aea
Change-Id: I00309bbe8bae525ea8f0ffc757b102f67fb1aa19

commit_message:
Remove server_groups_client from ignore_list

I75307176c2f032301da6227249070c42af54dd6e has fixed the method of
server_groups_client module which was against T110 rule.
So server_groups_client is not necessary in the ignore_list, then
this patch removes it.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

commit_message:
manual add/remove router for dvr_snat agent

This patch is to address the failure of manual move of
dvr_snat routers from one service node to another.

The entry in the csnat_l3_agent_bindings table is now removed
during the router to agent unbind operation.
Appropriate notification is now sent to the agent to remove
snat/qrouter namespace.

There were other places in the code
that needed to examine the snat binding table to
check if updates were required -
validate_agent_router_combination() and
check_agent_router_scheduling_needed().

Additionally, schedule_routers() was made optional
within the rpc _notification path since it can
override the manual move being attempted.

Conflicts:
        neutron/db/l3_agentschedulers_db.py

Co-Authored-By: Ila Palanisamy <ilavajuthy.palanisamy@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Oleg Bondarev <obondarev@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: Iac9598eb79f455c4ef3d3243a96bed524e3d2f7c
Closes-Bug: #1369721
(cherry picked from commit 7cfcbac066842e2d1dd3578e9eb5801bb4a1af34)

commit_message:
DVR: make sure snat portion is always scheduled when needed

commit 236e408272bcb9b8e957524864e571b5afdc4623 introduced
a regression where if router without external gateway was already
scheduled to all dvr_snat agents, then when adding external gateway
to the router, snat portion scheduling was skipped.
The patch fixes regression and adds corresponding unit (functional
in fact) test.

Closes-Bug: #1486627
Change-Id: Iad7e53bd57836f257d7110bc054d58029484ab99

commit_message:
DVR: fix router rescheduling on server side

This fixes router rescheduling for dvr routers to
correctly handle CSNAT portion rescheduling on server side.

Next patch will make L3 agent aware of possible SNAT role
rescheduling to/from it.

Partial-Bug: #1472205
Change-Id: I069500a2f1de9a734124544a3f2d793e9fa2d27c

commit_message:
API: use baymodel_ident to update a baymodel

Currently, we can not update a baymodel with baymodel name, this patch fixes
it by passing baymodel_ident instead of using baymodel_uuid.

Closes-Bug: #1516900
Change-Id: Ib372c06762fdb3918f391aefd25c43e6a2a5fca3

commit_message:
Correctly apply deciders across flow boundaries

When a flow is added to another flow and there is
a decider placed on that link we need to make sure
that we retain that decider.

This also ensures that any predecessor of that flow
that has a decider that affects the flow nodes execution
also gets used in the decision process.

Closes-Bug: #1515748

Change-Id: Ifdf20378b26cdd13e0a3ff87cec8990fe89c0661

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables
* Remove requirements.txt from deps, as this is
  already added automatically


Change-Id: Iecfbc050f3c261639cfa5c58aa69cf240708e198

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables

Change-Id: I7b586e228f4287eb4eeaa2f13cb8326a211e0517

'}, {'created': '2015-08-28 17:52:33.000000000', 'message': "Add native column-references into policy engine

Previously the policy engine assumed it had the schemas for
all datasources before it loaded rules from the database
or processed rule insertions from the user.  In particular,
any rule with a column-reference was compiled into a rule
without column-references, an operation that required
having the schemas available.

In the distributed architecture, we can no longer assume
the policy engine has access to schemas before rules
are loaded.  Schemas are sent via RPC calls from
datasources when they spin up.  Without any changes
to the policy engine to deal with schemas, the policy
engine would fail to boot if there were any rules
with column references.

This change makes the policy engine flexible enough to
load and process rules before the schemas arrive.  In
particular, the policy engine will now disable any
rule containing a column-reference for which the
schema is unknown.  Once all the appropriate schema
arrive, disabled rules are enabled.

Limitations of this change
- Schemas are set-once, i.e. once they are set they cannot
be set again.
- The policy engine does not check rules against the schemas
when they are set, except for disabled rules.
- Once a rule is disabled, the policy engine should probably
disable other rules because they rely on tables that are not
fully defined, but this functionality is not yet present.
- It is possible for a schema to come in that is inconsistent
with an existing disabled rule.  Such rules are stored in an
'error' datastructure, but there is no channel to the user to
inform them of these errors because the set-schema event
is caused not by the user but by the datasource driver.

Change-Id: I6aa1ff24d675d553d80a7d0fb9177fa8169e27a4

commit_message:
Add native column-references into policy engine

Previously the policy engine assumed it had the schemas for
all datasources before it loaded rules from the database
or processed rule insertions from the user.  In particular,
any rule with a column-reference was compiled into a rule
without column-references, an operation that required
having the schemas available.

In the distributed architecture, we can no longer assume
the policy engine has access to schemas before rules
are loaded.  Schemas are sent via RPC calls from
datasources when they spin up.  Without any changes
to the policy engine to deal with schemas, the policy
engine would fail to boot if there were any rules
with column references.

This change makes the policy engine flexible enough to
load and process rules before the schemas arrive.  In
particular, the policy engine will now disable any
rule containing a column-reference for which the
schema is unknown.  Once all the appropriate schema
arrive, disabled rules are enabled.

Limitations of this change
- Schemas are set-once, i.e. once they are set they cannot
be set again.
- The policy engine does not check rules against the schemas
when they are set, except for disabled rules.
- Once a rule is disabled, the policy engine should probably
disable other rules because they rely on tables that are not
fully defined, but this functionality is not yet present.
- It is possible for a schema to come in that is inconsistent
with an existing disabled rule.  Such rules are stored in an
'error' datastructure, but there is no channel to the user to
inform them of these errors because the set-schema event
is caused not by the user but by the datasource driver.

Change-Id: I6aa1ff24d675d553d80a7d0fb9177fa8169e27a4

commit_message:
Change col name for instance_id in nova:floatingIPS

Currently, listing floatingIPS in nova datasource shows host_id
as one of the column name which is rather confusing, as floating ip
is associated with instance rather than host. This commit is to
update the same to instance_id which sounds more apt than host_id.

Change-Id: I937a33e64988b11d6c83ade1153645b772df2130

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables
* Remove requirements.txt from deps, as this is
  already added automatically


Change-Id: I87c1fc87fb2a595b4453be6b33d679f0523cdea8

commit_message:
Choose virt type automatically

If nova_virt_type variable is not defined in defaults/main.yml,
Using command "egrep -c '(vmx|svm)' /proc/cpuinfo" in
deploy environment, it can easily tell us what the right
virt_type is according to the return value.

If this command returns a value of one or greater, your
compute node supports hardware acceleration and just set
virt_type = kvm.

If this command returns a value of zero, your compute node
does not support hardware acceleration and you must configure
virt_type = qemu instead of kvm.

Change-Id: I6e36ffcb56d50556df0803aea9f4cd7850fada5a
(cherry picked from commit 42bca0e390eb1cccbda6acabd231827ef798123f)

commit_message:
DVR: fix router scheduling

Fix scheduling of DVR routers to not stop scheduling once
csnat portion was scheduled. See bug report for failing
scenario.

This partially reverts
commit 3794b4a83e68041e24b715135f0ccf09a5631178
and fixes bug 1374473 by moving csnat scheduling
after general dvr router scheduling, so double binding does
not happen.

Closes-Bug: #1472163
Related-Bug: #1374473
(cherry picked from commit 236e408272bcb9b8e957524864e571b5afdc4623)

Conflicts:
        neutron/scheduler/l3_agent_scheduler.py
        neutron/tests/unit/extensions/test_agent.py
        neutron/tests/unit/plugins/openvswitch/test_agent_scheduler.py

Change-Id: I57c06e2be732e47b6cce7c724f6b255ea2d8fa32
