commit_message:
Fix dvr_local_router.floating_ip_added_dist failure after agent restart

If DVR is enabled and an l3-agent is restarted, associating a floatingip
to an existing vm on the compute node where the l3-agent was restarted
will fail.  This commit fixes the floating_ip_added_dist method in
dvr_local_router.py so that self.rtr_fip_subnet will be created if
it is 'None' prior to the attempt to call the get_name() method on
it.

Change-Id: I860ee3522275f62f393e66853e53ef387598983d
CLoses-Bug: #1515341

Remove psycopg2 useless requirement

commit_message:
Update list of modules supporting py34 tests

Currently, as neutron project supports py34 to a certain degree,
test_plugin and test_vpn_db modules also support py34.

All the modules in neutron-vpnaas support py34 finally.
So, we remove the enumeration of modules and test all modules.

Change-Id: Iba5cf0065ec9243fad90efcb192a66236a21bb2c
Closes-Bug: #1480326

[{'created': '2015-11-10 16:47:42.000000000', 'message': 'Set ZUUL_BRANCH using BRANCH if not available

In most cases, ZUUL_BRANCH is set in gate, but not all the time. One
exception is e.g. periodic stable jobs, where there is no actual patch
to validate, hence no ZUUL_REF or ZUUL_BRANCH is set. In that case, we
need to help zuul-cloner to determine the proper branch to fetch
neutron.

It could be achieved by e.g. hardcoding the branch using --zuul_branch
CLI argument passed into zuul-cloner. In this patch, I instead set
ZUUL_BRANCH to BRANCH that seems to be always present in all kinds of
jobs. It is then used by zuul-cloner to choose the correct branch.

This fixes the issue for stable/liberty periodic jobs for neutron-vpnaas
when we tried to validate it against neutron/master.

Change-Id: I360239a1443f8d4e16210a1ef743912e1bf85f41
'}]
commit_message:
Set ZUUL_BRANCH using BRANCH if not available

In most cases, ZUUL_BRANCH is set in gate, but not all the time. One
exception is e.g. periodic stable jobs, where there is no actual patch
to validate, hence no ZUUL_REF or ZUUL_BRANCH is set. In that case, we
need to help zuul-cloner to determine the proper branch to fetch
neutron.

It could be achieved by e.g. hardcoding the branch using --zuul_branch
CLI argument passed into zuul-cloner. In this patch, I instead set
ZUUL_BRANCH to BRANCH that seems to be always present in all kinds of
jobs. It is then used by zuul-cloner to choose the correct branch.

This fixes the issue for stable/liberty periodic jobs for neutron-vpnaas
when we tried to validate it against neutron/master.

Change-Id: I360239a1443f8d4e16210a1ef743912e1bf85f41

commit_message:
Do not use api-paste.ini osprofiler options

Starting with opsrofiler 0.3.1 release there is no need to set HMAC_KEYS
and ENABLED arguments in the api-paste.ini file, this can be set in the
heat.conf configuration file.

Change-Id: I77611c08d24839dc01766e994635cdb6a12922da

commit_message:
Distinguish project name and repo name

Currently, initials of project names are written with a lower case.
This patch set distinguishes project name of which initials are written with
a capital case, and repo name of which initials are written with a lower case.

e.g.) Nova
project name: Nova
repo name: nova

Change-Id: I3899c06e970946d219c81638e089148ae0d7eb3b

new rules so we can tackle them one at a time.

Use DEVICE_OWNER_* for 'network:*' constants

Now that we have the constant defined, we should reuse it from other
code to avoid potential typos.

commit_message:
Add a test for environment change in failed update

Add a functional test which verifies that adding a new resource during
an update, with a new custom resource type mapping in the environment,
allows for recovery when the update fails.

Change-Id: I7e52703b7f45c79a3a1434200d1e49988e78f333
Related-Bug: 1508096

commit_message:
Fix iptables modules references in rule generation

The way we were generating rules with module references
for TCP, UDP, and ICMP was not matching the output of
iptables-save so all of the counters for those rules
were being destroyed on each iptables reload.

This patch corrects the generation so it's in line with
iptables-save output. It uses the matching module name only
when a specific port number or port range is specified.
It also uses the full 'ipv6-icmp' protocol name that shows
up in the output rather than 'icmpv6'.

Closes-Bug: #1502924
Change-Id: I1bf9a85cd299a7618d29c72991612898c5437442
(cherry picked from commit 292bdff78b91320ea40739e1ceb01c3cb1a31cc8)

commit_message:
Cleanup dhcp namespace upon dhcp setup.

In some cases when more than 1 DHCP agents were assigned
to a network and then they became dead, their DHCP ports
become reserved. Later, when those agents revive or start
again, they acquire reserved ports, but it's not guaranteed
that they get exactly same ports. In such case DHCP agent
may create interface in the namespaces despite that another
interface already exist. In such case there will be two
hosts with dhcp namespaces each containing duplicate ports,
e.g. one port will be present on two hosts. This breaks
DHCP.

Closes-Bug: #1509959
Change-Id: I34eb1ad5c44dd3528c9910462e26536186e7a4fb
(cherry picked from commit 6ac43c119bff9da93f438d10033b209819a32230)

commit_message:
change some sentences to help understand

Pip install tempest will install a package from pip source, not from
a dir,so change it to pip install tempest/

Also change some sentences to help understand

Change-Id: I034b3e94fc35db40bd7f7f68ab20cdcbcfddbc37

Add installation procedure of cookiecutter to doc

Currently, in Usage, there is no installation procedure of cookiecutter.
This patch set adds installation procedure of cookiecutter to README.rst

commit_message:
Support new v2 API image filters

Provide support in Glance API for querying the image list for
created_at and updated_at times using guidance from the API Working
Group recommendations for filtering. Filtering is applied at the DB
layer.

DocImpact
ApiImpact
MitakaPriority
Change-Id: Ie94295bb82779ec17ab773928c71ae4a9ee8fbcc
Implements bp: v2-additional-filtering

commit_message:
Clean up hdisks after failed live migration

When there is a live migration failure that prevents the VM
from moving to the destination host, any hdisks created on the
destination host should be deleted. These hdisks are created
when we do the discovery operation for any volumes attached
to the VM via VSCSI.

Change-Id: I6e7f88ede68522c9f4788c549b8bfc84f7ae382a
(cherry picked from commit 09d23f8d3b13675f19b828e933aa36c3f3421cdf)

commit_message:
Make print_list accept a list of dict

Print_list() only accept a list of objects, it is useful to accept
a list of dicts

Change-Id: Icd4e37c88e8f88e67e66f8212fe5ed22e1c19b24

[{'created': '2015-09-29 20:37:00.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Nova Style API Version Support for Client

The Manila client needs the following changes to support microversions:

*   Maintain backwards compatibility with Kilo. When the client detects
    that the server doesn't support microversions it will fall back to
    using the v1 API.
*   The --os-share-api-version option supports overriding the version.
*   If 1.0 is specified as the version the client will load the v1
    client and use the server's v1 API.
*   The client will send a request for the server's API version and
    determine if the client's supported versions and the server's
    supported versions overlap. If not the client will display an error
    and quit. See diagram 1 below.
*   The client supports the @wraps annotation. The annotation is used
    with v2/shell.py commands to indicate the version supported by the
    command.
*   If an appropriate command version isn't found for commands using
    @wraps then the client will display an error and quit.

The files in the v2 directory include the latest available client code.
The files in the v1 directory represent the client code available in the
following commit: ab49d645befd04c84272f0d24e1b604012d191dd.

Diagram 1:
  Client:
         2.5           2.8
          |-------------|

  Server1:
     2.0           2.5
      |-------------|
     Client uses version 2.5

  Server2:
               2.7           2.10
                |-------------|
               Client uses version 2.8

  Server3:
                  2.9           2.12
                   |-------------|
                  Client displays error and quits

  Server4:
     1.0 (Kilo Server)
      |-|
     Client detects pre-microversion server and loads v1 client

Implements: blueprint manila-client-advanced-microversion-support

Change-Id: I3733fe85424e39566addc070d42609e508259f19

commit_message:
Nova Style API Version Support for Client

The Manila client needs the following changes to support microversions:

*   Maintain backwards compatibility with Kilo. When the client detects
    that the server doesn't support microversions it will fall back to
    using the v1 API.
*   The --os-share-api-version option supports overriding the version.
*   If 1.0 is specified as the version the client will load the v1
    client and use the server's v1 API.
*   The client will send a request for the server's API version and
    determine if the client's supported versions and the server's
    supported versions overlap. If not the client will display an error
    and quit. See diagram 1 below.
*   The client supports the @wraps annotation. The annotation is used
    with the v2/shell.py commands and any class that inherits from
    the Manager class in manilaclient/base.py.
*   If an appropriate command version isn't found for commands using
    @wraps then the client will display an error and quit.

following commit: ab49d645befd04c84272f0d24e1b604012d191dd.

Diagram 1:
  Client:
         2.5           2.8
          |-------------|

  Server1:
     2.0           2.5
      |-------------|
     Client uses version 2.5

  Server2:
               2.7           2.10
                |-------------|
               Client uses version 2.8

  Server3:
                  2.9           2.12
                   |-------------|
                  Client displays error and quits

  Server4:
     1.0 (Kilo Server)
      |-|
     Client detects pre-microversion server and loads v1 client

Example usage of wraps annotation:
*   Support 2.0 - 2.4: @api_versions.wraps("2.0", "2.4")
*   Support 2.5 - latest: @api_versions.wraps("2.5")

Implements: blueprint manila-client-advanced-microversion-support

Change-Id: I3733fe85424e39566addc070d42609e508259f19

[{'created': '2015-11-12 07:46:58.000000000', 'message': 'Sync with oslo-incubator

According to the latest agreement, apiclient and clituils will be
removed from Oslo incubator. We should keep the local copy by
ourselfs:
1. rename openstack/common/apiclient to common/apiclient
2. Delete unused part of apiclient
3. rename openstack/common/cliutils.py to common/clituils.py

commit_message:
Sync with oslo-incubator

According to the latest agreement in Oslo team, apiclient and
clituils will be removed from Oslo incubator. We should keep
the local copy by ourselfs:
1. rename openstack/common/apiclient to common/apiclient
2. Because Ironic only use base.py and exception.py, so delete others.
3. rename openstack/common/cliutils.py to common/clituils.py
4. Delete openstack/common/_i18n becuase we have common/i18n.py
5. Delete openstack folder because it is empty
6. Add related unit tests and add oslotest to test-requirements.

Change-Id: I9eecd0457e86e82e65db1d0bc9a4c5c0ed4bbf74

commit_message:
Add S3 signature v4 checking

Keystone can check signature v1 for s3,
but many new tools uses new v4 signature protocol.
This patchset adds checking of v4 signature.
Architecture of implementation is the same as
v1 implementated.

Change-Id: I14121b4df2cae1407102335671c3f6878d46fc35
Closes-Bug: #1473042

commit_message:
Fix rc cli to work with bay identifier

Fix replication controller cli to work with the bay identifier. As
part of object from bay changes we now create k8s objects per bay.
The server patches to take into consideration this change is in
review. This change passes bay_ident as a mandatory parameter to
the replication controller api's. Also, the URL is changed to
GET/PUT/POST/DEL data.

Partially-Implements: bp objects-from-bay

Change-Id: Ib65bac270da7056262000ffb2184af297e370daa

commit_message:
datetime.datetime.utcnow() should be replaced

timeutils.utcnow() should be used instead of datetime.datetime.now()
or datetime.datetime.utcnow()
This patch unifies it.
Closes-Bug: #1514748

Change-Id: Icb73746905612661cbda03e679fbfddd80bb6cc2

[{'created': '2015-11-10 22:08:34.000000000', 'message': 'Scrub orphan mappings pre-migration on source

Live migration can fail if orphan mappings associated with the migrating
LPAR exist on the source system.

This change set exploits the recently-added
pypowervm.tasks.storage.ScrubOrphanStorageForLpar, which will identify
such mappings for a specified LPAR ID, scrub them, and (for VSCSI
mappings) remove the associated storage if it is not still in use.

Change-Id: I747ad4063ebd5cb4effc565a4d255e325d454ffb
'}]
commit_message:
Scrub orphan mappings pre-migration on source

Live migration can fail if orphan mappings associated with the migrating
LPAR exist on the source system.

This change set exploits the recently-added
pypowervm.tasks.storage.ScrubOrphanStorageForLpar, which will identify
such mappings for a specified LPAR ID, scrub them, and (for VSCSI
mappings) remove the associated storage if it is not still in use.

Change-Id: I747ad4063ebd5cb4effc565a4d255e325d454ffb

I think I agree with Kyle's inline comment here, I'm not sure the default deprecation policy should include such a commitment. There has been a lot of cases in the past where a half-implemented feature or a driver were removed days before the final release so that we don't end up having to support it. There have also been cases where a something wrong was accidentally merged and quickly reverted. Having such a strict deprecation policy for unreleased features would prevent that. 

Now I understand that some projects want to optimize for CD and therefore want to offer deprecation guarantees beyond what the default policy mandates (and that is fine). I just don't think we can impose such a constraint on every project following the standard deprecation policy."}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2015-11-09 12:24:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

What plans do we have, to increase the community participation? Currently the top 145 contributors mentioned in the stat http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/fuel-group/90 are Mirantis employees.'}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2015-07-08 02:27:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

We recognize following barriers to entry for new contributors:

1) Creating custom Fuel builds: build environment for generating Fuel ISO images (https://docs.fuel-infra.org/fuel-dev/buildsystem.html) is difficult to set up, build scripts are hard to understand.

We plan to address that by modularising Fuel ISO build process into a hierarchy of reusable and configurable artifacts such as packages of individual Fuel components, and containerizing Fuel build environment. First step towards that goal is opening our packaging CI to public:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/fuel/+spec/public-packaging-ci

2) Using Fuel to deploy custom OpenStack versions: each Fuel release is tightly coupled with corresponding release of Mirantis OpenStack distribution.

We have started the process of decoupling Fuel from the OpenStack distribution, first milestone was achieved in Fuel 6.1 which enabled clean separation between different classes of package repositories, such as base Linux OS, OpenStack distribution, and Fuel itself:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/fuel/+spec/separate-mos-from-linux

Next step is enable deployment of OpenStack packages built from current tip of the upstream master branch:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/fuel/+spec/openstack-from-master

3) Learning Fuel core well enough to add new features without disrupting existing functionality.

To solve this problem, we have introduced the plugins framework (https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Fuel/Plugins) in Fuel 6.0. Now we are incrementally moving more and more capabilities from Fuel core to plugins, so that a wider range of problems can be solved entirely within a plugin, without impacting the core components of Fuel.

This has already enabled engineers from outside Mirantis to add non-trivial new capabilities to Fuel, such as:
https://github.com/stackforge/fuel-plugin-vxlan
https://github.com/dancn/fuel-plugin-calamari
https://github.com/stackforge/fuel-plugin-calico

We are also moving more discussions to OpenStack mailing lists and IRC channels in order to improve openness of our design and development processes. Emails about Fuel reported by Stackalytics per OpenStack release cycle:

 Grizzly: 0
 Havana: 9
 Icehouse: 94
 Juno: 437
 Kilo: 835'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-07-10 15:16:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

I'm happy to see that the efforts to align with others in areas where there is overlap and also to decouple from MOS are already under way.

As you look at modularization of ISO creation, I'd love to suggest a look (or maybe another look) at diskimage-builder, which in addition to supporting the TripleO project is used by several other projects to make project-specific image as well as by Infra to make all of the base images for the gate. If there is an output format you need that it doesn't do, I bet the team would take patches (I just added docker output support recently)

However, that's only a suggestion - there is absolutely no reason you must do that. Just - in a discussion about making modular building blocks for making images, it seems like an area ripe for collaboration."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-07-14 17:12:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-07-14 17:23:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

Fuel does seem to be another instance of diversity:danger'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2015-07-14 19:06:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2015-07-14 20:27:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote-1 Code-Review-1

Fuel does not use OpenStack's CI system at all.  There are no gate checks of any kind, not even pep8.  I understand it is difficult to test a deployment system in a virtualized environment, and I don't object to having additional CI systems to verify functionality under specific conditions.  But it would be good to establish a baseline deployment test in OpenStack's CI system.  Additionally, it should conform to the project testing interface and run code style and unit tests in OpenStack's CI system."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-07-14 20:31:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Rollcall-Vote'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-07-14 20:37:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

so, during the TC meeting, the lack of collaboration over the puppet modules came up as a real concern for me. I'd like to see action on that before I'm +1 here."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-07-14 20:41:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-07-14 20:49:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

My -1 is about Fuel's Puppet code.

Until I rose the issue [1], there was no real collaboration between Puppet OpenStack and Fuel groups. They are making progress and I'm sure they are doing their best. But intention is different from actual situation.To me, this is really too early to say it's an OpenStack project.
They still don't use our Puppet modules the right way (they have a RAW copy of code in the repository, instead of tracking a git URL using Puppetfile or whatever tool), their CI is not that open (a lot of internal URL that we can't access). I won't repeat all I said in the thread here, but in my position of Puppet OpenStack PTL, I disagree to have this project part of the big tent right now.

I sincerely hope they'll realize what they plan to do, which is being part of our community like other projects already succeed to do.

[1] https://www.mail-archive.com/openstack-dev@lists.openstack.org/msg55396.html"}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-07-14 20:53:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8797, 'date': '2015-07-15 00:17:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Emilien,

We've been working very hard on un-piling our huge pile of debt regarding the puppet module forks for over a year and a half here. I'm not sure what you're expecting here in terms of actions, commitment, or turn-around. Commitment is established, contribution is increased, ideas have been proposed, and modules that should be upstream proper are starting to move there.

Mirantis developers in the fuel-library component have picked up the pace. We have moved from #5 and 84 [1] reviews in Kilo cycle for puppet-openstack to #4 and 150 (by appearances, mostly in the last month) [2] We where at 36, and 37 reviews respectively for Juno and Icehouse.

Proposed items in discussions haven't received any feedback from you or other members of puppet-openstack. [3] This is a communication gap here, before we can start moving forward, a simple acknowledgment is necessary. We can't use a lazy consensus here.

The RAW copy from upstream was admittedly a bad technical decision from nearly 3 years ago. We are looking to resolve the problem in a productive manner but it will take a while to design, build and, test a new system for maintaining the modules. Alex S. has brought this up and sought feedback from the ML for this already [4]

The handling of murano module appears to be straightened out and is making progress forward[5], although appears stuck in governance review [6]

[1] http://stackalytics.com/?module=puppetopenstack-group&release=kilo

[2] http://stackalytics.com/?module=puppetopenstack-group&release=liberty

[3] https://www.mail-archive.com/openstack-dev@lists.openstack.org/msg55911.html (multiple proposals)

https://www.mail-archive.com/openstack-dev@lists.openstack.org/msg55889.html (asking if we want bugs cross triaged)

https://www.mail-archive.com/openstack-dev@lists.openstack.org/msg55770.html (proposal of packaging with patching option)

[4] https://www.mail-archive.com/openstack-dev%40lists.openstack.org/msg56657.html

[5] https://www.mail-archive.com/openstack-dev%40lists.openstack.org/msg56088.html

[6] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/192727/"}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-07-15 12:01:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Andrew,

> We've been working very hard on un-piling our huge pile of debt regarding the puppet module forks for over a year and a half here. I'm  not sure what you're expecting here in terms of actions, commitment, or turn-around. Commitment is established, contribution is increased, ideas have been proposed, and modules that should be upstream proper are starting to move there.

I have no doubt about your motivation, and I confirm things are moving. Though there is a difference between plans and actual situation.

> Mirantis developers in the fuel-library component have picked up the pace. We have moved from #5 and 84 [1] reviews in Kilo cycle for puppet-openstack to #4 and 150 (by appearances, mostly in the last month) [2] We where at 36, and 37 reviews respectively for Juno and Icehouse.

So your highlighting reviews metric, which means -1/+1 since you have no Puppet core in your group. This metric does mean anything to me because anyone is +1'ing patches from their colleagues (please look at some patches, and see all +1). I'm more interested in commits or bug fixes, that really show your code has been merged upstream and you fixed bugs for the community.
It takes 2 seconds to +1.
It takes more time to have a commit submitted and merged.
In Kilo, you have 26 commits in Puppet OpenStack modules: http://stackalytics.com/?module=puppetopenstack-group&release=kilo&metric=commits
In Liberty, you have 14 commits: http://stackalytics.com/?module=puppetopenstack-group&release=liberty&metric=commits
Same for resolved-bugs (16 to 7), same for personal day efforts (158 to 148).
We clearly see less contributions from Kilo to Liberty.

> Proposed items in discussions haven't received any feedback from you or other members of puppet-openstack. [3] This is a communication gap here, before we can start moving forward, a simple acknowledgment is necessary. We can't use a lazy consensus here.

The end of the thread was kind of consensus to me and I was pretty happy to see Dmitry was really open to the discussion.

> The RAW copy from upstream was admittedly a bad technical decision from nearly 3 years ago. We are looking to resolve the problem in a productive manner but it will take a while to design, build and, test a new system for maintaining the modules. Alex S. has brought this up and sought feedback from the ML for this already [4]

I technically doubt it will take some time, many products already use Puppet modules, and there is many ways to manage that, we already covered that in the thread. This is to me a technical issue because the code is really duplicated and not pulled, which is to me a blocker to be an OpenStack project, because it overlaps with our code.

> The handling of murano module appears to be straightened out and is making progress forward[5], although appears stuck in governance review [6]

If you read the history of the governance patch, I +1'ed and I'm very happy we made it together.

Our group is really small comparing to Fuel team, I would really love to see more community commitment in the future:

* help us to elaborate blueprints
* participate (not only +1 for also negative reviews) at reading our code
* help us more and more in bug triage (you already made progress, very appreciated)
* help us to improve our CI (using OpenStack Infra and not internal servers that we can't access)
* bring your expertise in our group, I've seen a lot of cool stuffs in Fuel (docker, etc...). Why not helping us to bring it upstream?
* being really part of the group, be involved in code design, discussions and decisions.

Once I'll see real improvements on the last points, I'll be very happy to have Fuel part of OpenStack, but until now, I still think Fuel is a product managed by Mirantis, and not an Open-Source project build by OpenStack community.

Even if my -1 does not count here as a Rollcall-Vote because I'm not part of the Technical Committee, I wanted to share my thoughts about the actual situation.

Regards,
Emilien Macchi"}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-07-15 12:07:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review Rollcall-Vote-1

Updating my vote to reflect the TC meeting yesterday. I'd like to see real motion on getting CI integrated with Infra, and on the puppet module resync. I think Fuel is great and a benefit to the community - but I think we have to get at least some steps forward towards the community part."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-07-15 12:22:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote-1

I agree with what Monty just said.

I do think adding Fuel is fine and think we should revisit this later in the cycle to see how things are going.'}, {'account_id': 7822, 'date': '2015-07-15 15:25:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Voicing my concerns from yesterday. The Fuel project is composed of a number of pre-existing open source projects that have been forked from their original source. These include but are not limited to the recently "big-tent" graduated puppet-openstack modules. Mailing list conversations support the idea the Fuel forked these projects for commercial expediency, which runs against the spirit of open collaboration. It sets a precedent where new projects can be forks of existing projects, encouraging fragmentation rather than collaboration. I strongly feel that as a precondition to being admitted as a big tent project Fuel needs move to composing from upstream rather than massively forking both OpenStack and non-OpenStack projects. There is precedent for this. In the puppet-openstack project world we were not allowed to merge puppet-ovs into stackforge until we communicated with all of the existing forks and reached agreement to make the stackforge/puppet-ovs project the preferred upstream source.'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2015-07-15 17:18:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review -Rollcall-Vote'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-07-17 11:55:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This is exactly this kind of behavior that do not show a full commitment to contribute to Puppet OpenStack modules yet: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/198119/

The patch is not merged upstream, so Fuel's team is fixing it in Fuel packaging. So puppet-horizon is 'broken' but they don't really care.
Even with the great feedback of Horizon's team, the review has no more activity.

Quote: "issue was fixed in package https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/9170/"

Andrew, how do you explain this?'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-07-17 14:36:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Emilien, thanks for the heads up about an obvious failure of working with the upstream Puppet-OpenStack community. We'll use this example in our lessons learned.

-jay"}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2015-07-18 23:54:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Trying to explore and address all concerns raised in the review comments here creates a risk of making this discussion impossible to follow. Instead, I've started several separate threads on openstack-dev for all major points of contention. 

I've proposed a plan on how Fuel can adopt the project testing interface:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/069908.html

Assuming that what I've described as Stage 4 is sufficient to meet the TC requirements, PTI support across all Fuel components can optimistically be done in December 2015, conservatively in August 2016. The first result, getting PTI for just one component, can be done in a month.

I've announced that we'll try puppet-librarian approach to reusing upstream Puppet modules:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/069906.html

Once again, we can get one or two modules at best integrated that way at first (we'll know the results next week), and if that works out we'll make that mandatory for the next Fuel release.

Finally, I've reviewed the current state of collaboration between Fuel and Puppet OpenStack teams:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/069925.html

I've found evidence of much more than just "intent", I see both massive (7x!) increase in effort spent by Fuel team in pushing patches to Puppet OpenStack in just the last month and a half, and a significant push back (at least from Emilien) in getting these patches landed. I see Fuel developers giving each other's commits -1 votes. I see them responding to reviews within a single day and staying active in stuck reviews for months.

I also see that the patch https://review.openstack.org/198119 that Emilien has used as a negative example clearly shows evidence that Fuel developers listened to the feedback from Horizon and Puppet OpenStack cores, went back to the drawing board, and moved the fix from puppet to packaging, because that's what they were told to do, and because it was the right thing to do.

Sure, there's still a long way to go, but summarily dismissing all results and efforts that are already evident as merely "intent" or "plans" is counterproductive to the open and friendly collaboration between projects.'}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2015-07-19 00:07:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-21 12:31:27.000000000', 'content': 'Topic changed from fuel to formal-vote'}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2015-10-26 22:04:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2015-10-26 22:06:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Over the past several months, Fuel team has been working hard to address the concerns the Technical Committee has raised about our proposal.

To sum up, following issues were identified back in July:

* Lack of PTI conformance.
* Code duplication with the Puppet OpenStack project.
* Insufficient collaboration with the Puppet OpenStack project.

I have recently reported our progress with setting up voting gate jobs for Fuel repositories and reviewed the state of our collaboration with Puppet OpenStack team:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-October/077777.html 
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-October/077824.html

While there's still room for improvement (isn't here always?), I think we've reached the point where the above three issues are under control."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-26 22:07:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

As a Puppet OpenStack PTL, I recognize the huge efforts from Fuel team to contribute back to Puppet modules.
We really appreciate that and we hope we will continue that way.
My +1 is because I think their Puppet part of Fuel is now using upstream work.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-11-09 09:57:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote+1

(2 comments)

The Fuel team has gone through great lengths over the past months to collaborate with existing projects, reduce overlap and adopt the OpenStack ways. My current opinion is it has reached now the point where it can be considered a product of the OpenStack community, but YMMV.

The fuel folks have done a lot of work to move to OpenStack's CI system, which is great.  There is still quite a bit of private CI happening though, much of it unecessary.  There are still quite a few docs, syntax checks, etc, that could be run upstream.  It's also possible that some of the complex multi-host jobs might be able to run on OpenStack infra as well -- I'm not certain whether that's actually been discussed in technical detail.

At any rate, progress in this area is good, but incomplete.  I am happy with the intent and direction, but would like to see this aspect more complete before approval."}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2015-11-10 19:48:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

There's actually not that many gaps left to close before Fuel can claim to be fully PTI compliant. We kept working on it since my previous report (linked above) and will continue in the forseeable future.

Changes since October 23:

* fuel-library is now gated with syntax checks and unit tests
* fuel-qa is now gated with pep8 jobs (this is a repository with tests so it doesn't have unit tests)
* fuel-ostf (already gated with pep8) now has gevent [0] and can move forward with python jobs

[0] https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:merged+branch:master+topic:support_gevent,n,z

Total voting gate jobs across fuel repositories: 35

Ready to enable voting (6 jobs):

* gate jobs (-pep8 and -python27) for new repos: fuel-menu, network-checker, shotgun

Still in progress (7 jobs):

* fix gate-fuel-agent-docs, gate-fuel-docs-docs
* create gate-fuel-ostf-python27
* create gate-fuel-astute-ruby21 and -syntax
* create gate-fuel-nailgun-agent-ruby21 and -syntax

It will take a few more weeks to finish the above, but there's no fundamental blockers left. The core components (fuel-web and fuel-library) are fully covered, remaining gaps are in non-core repositories and we're actively working on closing them, it doesn't make sense for us to stop now that we've come so far.

We have some duplicate jobs of the above left running in Fuel CI, but I don't think this counts as PTI violation. Needless to say, we plan remove Fuel CI jobs that duplicate the jobs we've got running on OpenStack Infra.

Running Fuel's complex multi-node tests on OpenStack Infra would be nice, but also not a PTI requirement, and will likely take months of work on both ends (adjusting the tests and improving nodepool and other OpenStack Infra tools), which is why in my original plan from July [1] I've placed it at Stage 6 (stretch goal for distant future). Based on the current state of multi-node testing on OpenStack Infra as discussed in Tokyo [2], my understanding is that neither functionality nor capacity is there in OpenStack Infra to run the multi-node deployment tests from fuel-qa.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/069908.html

[2] https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/mitaka-cross-project-multinode-testing"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-11-10 20:09:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

I feel the Fuel contributor community has done its absolute best to align with upstream (both infra and Puppet-OpenStack) communities, and to be open and transparent in reporting on the status of progress.

I see no reason not to welcome Fuel into the big tent. If we don't, I feel we are holding the Fuel project to a set of requirements that we are not forcing other projects to meet.

-jay"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-11-10 20:10:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote-1

[{'created': '2015-07-07 19:43:11.000000000', 'message': 'Add Fuel to OpenStack Projects

Fuel is an open source deployment and management tool for OpenStack.
Fuel's mission is to streamline and accelerate the otherwise
time-consuming, often complex, and error-prone process of deploying,
testing and maintaining various configurations of OpenStack at scale.

Fuel has been successfully used to deploy OpenStack in environments
ranging from personal proof-of-concept micro-clouds to production
infrastructures composed of hundreds of nodes running tens of thousands
of instances, using a wide variety of network and storage backends, with
out-of-the-box support of most OpenStack projects. Fuel was used by many
successful competitors in the Rule The Stack competition in Vancouver:
https://01.org/openstack/openstacksummitvancouverbc2015/rule-stack-vancouver-results

Fuel is an enabler technology for integration of OpenStack with other
cloud computing initiatives, such as Ceph, OPNFV, Kubernetes:
https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BxYswyvIiAEZUEp4aWJPYVNjeU0/view
https://wiki.opnfv.org/get_started/open_questions#installer_comparison
http://googlecloudplatform.blogspot.com/2015/02/run-container-based-applications-on-OpenStack-with-Kubernetes.html

According to OpenStack user survey before the Liberty OpenStack Summit
(answers collected in March-April 2015), Fuel is the #3 deployment tool
used to set up OpenStack:
http://superuser.openstack.org/articles/openstack-users-share-how-their-deployments-stack-up

Below is a summary of the state of Fuel project's compliance with the
OpenStack Projects requirements as defined in:
http://governance.openstack.org/reference/new-projects-requirements.html

Alignment with OpenStack Mission: Fuel provides a REST API, a web UI, a
command line interface, and plugin framework that automate and simplify
deployment and operation of cloud infrastructures based on OpenStack.

The OpenStack way ("the 4 opens"):

  Open Source: All Fuel components are licensed under Apache License
  v2.0. Fuel does not have library dependencies that restrict how the
  project may be distributed or deployed.

  Open Community: Fuel core reviewers are approved by contributors of
  the project. Fuel project holds weekly IRC meetings on OpenStack
  channels with public meeting agenda, minutes, and logs, since
  February 2014:
  http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/fuel/

  Open Development: Fuel uses public code reviews on OpenStack
  infrastructure since September 2013:
  https://review.openstack.org/46666

  Commits to all Fuel repositories are approved by core reviewers and
  validated with automated tests on publicly accessible CI:
  https://ci.fuel-infra.org/

  Fuel project has appointed Andrew Woodward as a Community Ambassador
  to serve as a liaison with other OpenStack projects.

  Fuel developers actively engage other OpenStack projects for
  collaboration on topics ranging from high availability to storage:
  http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/ha-guide/90
  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-July/040484.html

  Fuel project is implemented primarily in Python, adjusts its Python
  dependencies for compliance with OpenStack global requirements, and
  works on reconciling its differences with OpenStack Puppet modules:
  https://blueprints.launchpad.net/fuel/+spec/automate-the-verification-of-compliance-openstack-global-requirement
  https://lwn.net/Articles/648331/

  Open Design: Fuel uses openstack-dev mailing list with [Fuel] tag for
  development discussions. All feature development for Fuel is managed
  via blueprints in Launchpad and specifications in the fuel-specs
  repository on OpenStack infrastructure:
  https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Fuel/How_to_contribute#Subscribe_to_mailing_lists
  https://blueprints.launchpad.net/fuel/
  https://review.openstack.org/#/q/project:stackforge/fuel-specs,n,z

Interoperability with the rest of OpenStack: Fuel REST API and its CLI
and web frontends use Keystone for authentication. Fuel REST API has an
overlap with Tuskar, Fuel team would be happy to work with the Tuskar
community on a long-term alignment of APIs if the Technical Committee
determined such a step would be preferable.

Active team: As of July 7, 2015, Fuel project has 23 core reviewers
posting 54.5 reviews per day, and over 200 active contributors:
http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/fuel-group/90

Change-Id: I8c6579f84a42324eaacae52e459b51c4e7b92b56

According to OpenStack user survey before the Liberty OpenStack Summit
(answers collected in March-April 2015), Fuel is the #3 deployment tool
used to set up OpenStack:
http://superuser.openstack.org/articles/openstack-users-share-how-their-deployments-stack-up

Below is a summary of the state of Fuel project's compliance with the
OpenStack Projects requirements as defined in:
http://governance.openstack.org/reference/new-projects-requirements.html

Alignment with OpenStack Mission: Fuel provides a REST API, a web UI, a
command line interface, and plugin framework that automate and simplify
deployment and operation of cloud infrastructures based on OpenStack.

The OpenStack way ("the 4 opens"):

  Open Source: All Fuel components are licensed under Apache License
  v2.0. Fuel does not have library dependencies that restrict how the
  project may be distributed or deployed.

  Open Community: Fuel core reviewers are approved by contributors of
  the project. Fuel project holds weekly IRC meetings on OpenStack
  channels with public meeting agenda, minutes, and logs, since
  February 2014:
  http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/fuel/

  Open Development: Fuel uses public code reviews on OpenStack
  infrastructure since September 2013:
  https://review.openstack.org/46666

  Commits to all Fuel repositories are approved by core reviewers and
  validated with automated tests on publicly accessible CI:
  https://ci.fuel-infra.org/

  Fuel project has appointed Andrew Woodward as a Community Ambassador
  to serve as a liaison with other OpenStack projects.

  Fuel developers actively engage other OpenStack projects for
  collaboration on topics ranging from high availability to storage:
  http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/ha-guide/90
  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-July/040484.html

  Fuel project is implemented primarily in Python, adjusts its Python
  dependencies for compliance with OpenStack global requirements, and
  works on reconciling its differences with OpenStack Puppet modules:
  https://blueprints.launchpad.net/fuel/+spec/automate-the-verification-of-compliance-openstack-global-requirement
  https://lwn.net/Articles/648331/

  Open Design: Fuel uses openstack-dev mailing list with [Fuel] tag for
  development discussions. All feature development for Fuel is managed
  via blueprints in Launchpad and specifications in the fuel-specs
  repository on OpenStack infrastructure:
  https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Fuel/How_to_contribute#Subscribe_to_mailing_lists
  https://blueprints.launchpad.net/fuel/
  https://review.openstack.org/#/q/project:stackforge/fuel-specs,n,z

Interoperability with the rest of OpenStack: Fuel REST API and its CLI
and web frontends use Keystone for authentication. Fuel REST API has an
overlap with Tuskar, Fuel team would be happy to work with the Tuskar
community on a long-term alignment of APIs if the Technical Committee
determined such a step would be preferable.

Active team: As of July 7, 2015, Fuel project has 23 core reviewers
posting 54.5 reviews per day, and over 200 active contributors:
http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/fuel-group/90

commit_message:
Add Fuel to OpenStack Projects

Fuel is an open source deployment and management tool for OpenStack.
Fuel's mission is to streamline and accelerate the otherwise
time-consuming, often complex, and error-prone process of deploying,
testing and maintaining various configurations of OpenStack at scale.

Fuel has been successfully used to deploy OpenStack in environments
ranging from personal proof-of-concept micro-clouds to production
infrastructures composed of hundreds of nodes running tens of thousands
of instances, using a wide variety of network and storage backends, with
out-of-the-box support of most OpenStack projects. Fuel was used by many
successful competitors in the Rule The Stack competition in Vancouver:
https://01.org/openstack/openstacksummitvancouverbc2015/rule-stack-vancouver-results

Fuel is an enabler technology for integration of OpenStack with other
cloud computing initiatives, such as Ceph, OPNFV, Kubernetes:
https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BxYswyvIiAEZUEp4aWJPYVNjeU0/view
https://wiki.opnfv.org/get_started/open_questions#installer_comparison
http://googlecloudplatform.blogspot.com/2015/02/run-container-based-applications-on-OpenStack-with-Kubernetes.html

According to OpenStack user survey before the Liberty OpenStack Summit
(answers collected in March-April 2015), Fuel is the #3 deployment tool
used to set up OpenStack:
http://superuser.openstack.org/articles/openstack-users-share-how-their-deployments-stack-up

Below is a summary of the state of Fuel project's compliance with the
OpenStack Projects requirements as defined in:
http://governance.openstack.org/reference/new-projects-requirements.html

Alignment with OpenStack Mission: Fuel provides a REST API, a web UI, a
command line interface, and plugin framework that automate and simplify
deployment and operation of cloud infrastructures based on OpenStack.

The OpenStack way ("the 4 opens"):

  Open Source: All Fuel components are licensed under Apache License
  v2.0. Fuel does not have library dependencies that restrict how the
  project may be distributed or deployed.

  Open Community: Fuel core reviewers are approved by contributors of
  the project. Fuel project holds weekly IRC meetings on OpenStack
  channels with public meeting agenda, minutes, and logs, since
  February 2014:
  http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/fuel/

  Open Development: Fuel uses public code reviews on OpenStack
  infrastructure since September 2013:
  https://review.openstack.org/46666

  Commits to all Fuel repositories are approved by core reviewers and
  validated with automated tests on publicly accessible CI:
  https://ci.fuel-infra.org/

  Fuel project has appointed Andrew Woodward as a Community Ambassador
  to serve as a liaison with other OpenStack projects.

  Fuel developers actively engage other OpenStack projects for
  collaboration on topics ranging from high availability to storage:
  http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/ha-guide/90
  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-July/040484.html

  Fuel project is implemented primarily in Python, adjusts its Python
  dependencies for compliance with OpenStack global requirements, and
  works on reconciling its differences with OpenStack Puppet modules:
  https://blueprints.launchpad.net/fuel/+spec/automate-the-verification-of-compliance-openstack-global-requirement
  https://lwn.net/Articles/648331/

  Open Design: Fuel uses openstack-dev mailing list with [Fuel] tag for
  development discussions. All feature development for Fuel is managed
  via blueprints in Launchpad and specifications in the fuel-specs
  repository on OpenStack infrastructure:
  https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Fuel/How_to_contribute#Subscribe_to_mailing_lists
  https://blueprints.launchpad.net/fuel/
  https://review.openstack.org/#/q/project:stackforge/fuel-specs,n,z

Interoperability with the rest of OpenStack: Fuel REST API and its CLI
and web frontends use Keystone for authentication. Fuel REST API has an
overlap with Tuskar, Fuel team would be happy to work with the Tuskar
community on a long-term alignment of APIs if the Technical Committee
determined such a step would be preferable.

Active team: As of July 7, 2015, Fuel project has 23 core reviewers
posting 54.5 reviews per day, and over 200 active contributors:
http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/fuel-group/90

Change-Id: I8c6579f84a42324eaacae52e459b51c4e7b92b56

* Configure in Hiera neutron::server::notifications::* parameters.
* non-ha: include ::neutron::server::notifications
* ha: include ::neutron::server::notifications and create orchestration
* Set vif_plugging_is_fatal to True so we actually fail if Neutron is not
  able to create the VIF during Nova server creation workflow.

BZ-1264740

commit_message:
neutron: enable nova-event-callback by default

* Add NovaApiVirtualIP string parameter.
* Compute nova_url and nova_admin_auth_url parameters.
* Configure in Hiera neutron::server::notifications::* parameters.
* non-ha: include ::neutron::server::notifications
* ha: include ::neutron::server::notifications and create orchestration
* Set vif_plugging_is_fatal to True so we actually fail if Neutron is not
  able to create the VIF during Nova server creation workflow.

Depends-On: I21dc10396e92906eab4651c318aa2ee62a8e03c7
Change-Id: I02e41f87404e0030d488476680af2f6d45af94ff

commit_message:
Remove 'Retry-After' in server create and resize

Base on following discussion
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072344.html
we need to avoid Retry-After when HTTPForbidden is returned
to server create and resize functions.

Change-Id: Icf5a78224ac0dd597fa930f5a8eb3dd7d1c0142c
Closes-Bug: 1486635

Thanks for this!

I'm -1ing because I feel like the current formula picks up project teams that may not be "diverse", but are not dangerously non-diverse. That includes Zaqar and Sahara, the problem seems to lie with the core reviewers thresholds.

For example if a company has 60% of core reviewers and another 40% of core reviewers, that triggers the core_reviews_top2 and core_reviewers_top2 thresholds. I wouldn't consider that team "diverse", but I wouldn't say it's not dangerously non-diverse.

How about we remove the core_reviews_top2 and core_reviewers_top2 thresholds and bump the core_reviews and core_reviewers thresholds to 85% or 90% ? That would spare Zaqar, TripleO, Congress and Sahara, which all do not strike me as dangerously non-diverse.

is the idea of this tag to promote broader contributions so that one/two companies don't completely lock down a project? tbh, this (and the original diversity tag) seems like an over-simplification of many, many conditional factors.

branding something based on a handful of selectively chosen criteria is probably the worse way to encourage diversity. it makes it easy for individuals to lazily make assumptions rather than actually examine whether a project is inviting/open/collaborative or not.

if an open project has a large chunk of the contributors pull out because a company decides to be less open, it seems wrong to brand the project as not diverse. similarly, in any given cycle, a company may need to grab it's developers to work on non-community work full-time and therefore minimising their contributions.

I think it's fine if the name is judgmental, and if it's not the precise opposite of "diverse-affiliation". Both tags serve different purposes (answer different questions).

diverse-affiliation lets you know that the project has a lot of different organizations behind it, so it has mindshare. So it looks like it has a bright future.

danger-not-diverse lets you know that the project is in immediate danger of disappearing completely if one single person (CEO of the main org supporting its development) decides that it's not worth pursuing anymore. So use at your own risk.

Both are valuable pieces of information to communicate to our downstream users.

There are projects that are not produced by a very diverse community but still are not in immediate danger. Those have no tags applied.'}, {'account_id': 11437, 'date': '2015-09-11 22:45:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

There have been some additional repos imported into TripleO recently, and with the stats re-run, it appears to me that this tag would be applied to TripleO. Given that, I do think it's accurate that TripleO should have this tag applied (once the wording is worked out).

I don't however feel that the first 3 items in the bullet list for the tag definition apply to TripleO, only the last. So, that's basically what's framing my comments. I do stand by them as generally applicable to what I think is best for OpenStack however.

And apologies, I know this has already come full circle and the "possible risk" criteria were actually added in a later patchset. Personally, I liked how it was originally worded, with perhaps the addition of one thing we can say concretely about low diversity:

- if the single backing company were to drop support, the project would be moribound

In essence, I think we should stick to tags that say concrete things with certainty VS. having tags that mean possible things. So, if we want a tag that means:

 * "danger - poor adoption and investment in the project"

Then let's definitely have one.

But let's not have a tag that means:

 * "danger - POSSIBLE poor adoption and investment in the project".

The challenge would be figuring out how to apply the former objectively. While the definition might be subjective to some ("danger"), it is either applied or not, and the definition is concrete. And that's really key to keeping ourselves honest on maintaining the balance between objective tag application and subjective tag definition. But, as soon as we say, a valid tag definition means it can say things that are only "possible", then we've really lost a lot of significance of the objective application of the tag. What does it even mean for a tag to be applied at that point? Possible poor adoption and investment is a risk to all projects, diverse or not.

That being said, I have no problem with danger in the name. As it is a real danger if a single backing company were to drop support for a non-diverse project.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-09-18 03:01:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Which becomes a reason never to fix anything in those projects' culture.'}, {'account_id': 11437, 'date': '2015-09-21 15:57:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

@Jay: I disagree that they're not risks, but perhaps rephrasing makes it better. See below.

@Eoghan: to be fair to @jogo, I wrote those words. Here they are, unexcerpted:
----
A project with this tag has small number of interests driving the majority of the project's development. This can indicate several possible risks:

* the project is young and hasn't gained adoption yet
* poor adoption and investment in the project
* an unhealthy collaborative environment in the project
* the danger that the project could become moribund due to the budgeting decisions of a single company
----

A potential adopter or developer, seeing this tag, will likely be asking themselves, "Should I adopt/join? Why is this not a diverse project?" In writing the four cases above, I aimed to give four clear answers. Spelled out more clearly as risks vs. reasons:

* The risk that, as a young project, it's not yet stable enough to adopt.
* The risk that this project is declining in popularity and/or developer interest such that adoption will lead to the eventual need for replacement.
* The risk that the current project team is in some way driving away people with diverse viewpoints, either in adoption or development
* The risk that the current team de-investing in the project will end active development entirely.

All that said, I'm fine if you want to cut any or all of that. It was an attempt to be explicit about the risks that this tag is calling out; if any of those seem not in line with what we're aiming to do here, chuck it. =]'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-09-22 13:00:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

I definitely appreciate, and agree with the point of having a supportive OpenStack community.

I also think it's really important that we do call things out that we consider problems. We've got a -1 button on gerrit for this reason. Giving negative feedback shouldn't be an issue if you provide clear direction on how to remove that negative feedback.

Single company open source is the new closed source. It is fine that projects might start in that state because everything has to start somewhere. However it's really important that projects in that situation make it their top priority to expand their base.

I feel that if we don't flag projects in this situation, they won't realize this is their most pressing issue. Because the project leadership doesn't internalize this, they won't focus on making their project more inclusive of others. This creates swaths of the OpenStack ecosystem where new comers are not welcome. 

Some times being supportive, and building a supportive ecosystem requires saying a thing needs to change. Saying that we all believe they need to change, but we won't express that directly seems more passive aggressive than supportive. 

The role of the TC is to manage the whole community. I think providing direct feedback that a thing isn't right to project leadership on a handful of projects for the benefit of future contributors and users is part of that responsibility."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-10-09 10:07:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

I left a comment inline bike shedding on the name a bit, which I'll continue here.

I think the currently proposed name "single-vendor" is fine. It conveys that, if a single company is behind an open source project, they are probably selling it or something related to it, and as a consumer of that open source project, one may want to be aware of that. That's great.

Changing the name to "single-organization" moves away from that meaning. We don't track a contributor's "organization affiliation", we track their "corporate affiliation" - and we track this for several reasons which are related to this tag.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-11-13 09:55:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Rollcall-Vote+1

(I could go with both, but I think if a given organization is the single group caring about a given project, it de-facto becomes the "vendor" for this project. commit_message:
Add team:single-vendor tag

Objectively communicates when project teams are driven by a single
organization, so that this fact can be taken into account in project
adoption decisions.

Change-Id: I399046ab7c3266b08c2a48382abfb89c33aab146

commit_message:
Use dockerctl start for supervisorctl container launch

If docker daemon is restarted, the mount points are not safely
torn down. dockerctl cleans these up before trying to start
the container and therefore should be used.

There was an original change to use direct docker commands
because you could not start a container from a different
Fuel release, but now this is possible and works. Therefore,
this patch depends on the patch that fixes it.

Depends-On: Ia864b0a9843f927aa85945e5ab0b2da4bec3a440
Change-Id: Ie3e471d1c394fac9228b7e2bf4b6877775680b3b
Closes-Bug: #1511294

thanks for the quick follow up'}, {'account_id': 12715, 'date': '2015-09-21 19:18:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So, one of the downsides of switching to the IPA based ramdisk for inspection is that we do not have many "collectors" created for it yet.

The upside of that is that it takes almost no time...even on the HA job it took about 2 minutes total.

Given that, and the fact that the collectors are plugins that can be disabled, I think we should keep this minimum level of inspection on all jobs. commit_message:
Turn introspection back on

There should not be a difference in introspection results
on the different jobs, so introspection is only enabled on
the nonha job.

This change lowers the timeout for introspection to 10
minutes, as it should not take that long with the switch
to IPA ramdisk.

Change-Id: I152310d2ba1f239df9b890d48044efce8185fad6

have few questions, I hope to get clarified in the process of working on SFC in Neutron. I apologize if some of them are lost on me only. 
1) how will it be coordinated with  a mech driver that implements VXLAN, for example? i.e. can one build a service chain on top of an Overlay? What parameters will have to passed to the Overlay to make it happen (this is what we are discussing...)? I assume that the need to pass parameters is common to all options UNLESS the whole network is directly managed by Neutron which is not where we are...
2) now suppose, one would like to support an IETF draft like NSH (or Geneve if it gets some public TLV definitions), how do you do it (related to number 1 above)? (using NSH as an example as it has a very elaborate and std based SFC as well as a working open source implementation)
3) What policy can be expressed in Neutron today - SG is limited to ACL... how can one express a more flex policy than go to the next port and only the next port?
4) what about ability to change the SFC graph by an SF (vs a user/admin)? What about dynamic load distribution  - what takes the role of an SFF? 
5) how can metadata be passed along ?
6) how to create loops or forks (multi-way fan out)?
7) How fast and scalable is the Security group for this dynamic task (Enterprise ACL are more static and many policies address a broad range of traffic, so fewer rules)'}, {'account_id': 6598, 'date': '2015-06-28 23:39:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(2 comments)

few questions inline'}, {'account_id': 16257, 'date': '2015-06-29 05:19:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I'd like to point out a possible gaps in this proposal, based on many conversations with customer and long field experience.

1) In almost every type of 'service', which ever it might be (fw, lb, ips, etc), there are typically a service policy definition(s) that user would like to specify when using a service. These policies dictate 'how' a service should function depending on the business use case requirements.

Typically, just redirecting the traffic to a service is not sufficient and specifying the service policy in context is highly desirable.

To that extend, the ability to specify context meta data must be added for each leg of a chain. This context will include a reference tag that would be meaningful to the service's data plane component and would be mapped to the service policy in context.

So per above, the original packets needs to be wrapped using some encapsulation technique, such as VLAN, QINQ, MPLS, VXLAN, NSH, GRE, etc. The type of encapsulation to use is really dictated by the service function and the switch support capabilities. It is possible to require that service function and switching component register their supported format, but this will add complexity. Initially, we can just have the user specify which encapsulation type to use based on their knowledge on what is supported in their environment.

2) A service function may expose one vNIC to handle both ingress and egress traffic (as oppose to a pair). There is no real reason why there must always be a pair as a single interface can really handle both. In this case, packets has to be tagged with direction bit so that data plane can tell if a packet is incoming or outgoing from the perspective of the chain direction. This flag must also be included in the encapsulation header.

3) As per call for meta data from above #1 and #2, there has be an encapsulation format contract so that data plane knows how to read the "service policy tag" and "direction" flag (and maybe additional other information in the future). As it is possible that different service function may support need different set of meta data formats and depending on the encapsulation type chosen, there needs to be an encapsulation format descriptor defined per chain.

4) A highly requested capability is to capture the notion of "service function chain wiring failure policy", i.e. - What happen if my service function instance is not available? should we continue forward packets to the next hop in the chain (fail_open)?, or should we drop all packets (fail_close)? Depending on the business requirement, user may want to customize this behaviour. The notion of what constitute service function instance unavailability can be complicated and may require specific heart bit customization for each service, but we can start with a very simple notion of service function ports are down (typically because service function instance VM is down). This should be easily detectable by the network fabric and Neutron.


To summarize, it would be good to consider the above requirements by allowing additional attribute at the port chain leg definition. More specifically, the proposed CLI/API should include the following optional arguments: encapsulation_type (enum: VLAN, QINQ, MPLS, VXLAN, NSH, GRE, etc), encasulation_format (enum: TBD), service_policy_tag (32 bit number), chaining_failure_policy_type (bit 0=fail_open, 1=fail_close).'}, {'account_id': 11313, 'date': '2015-06-29 20:08:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11907, 'date': '2015-06-30 18:22:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Here are my answers to Uri's questions: 
1) Yes, the API allows you to build a service chain on top of an Overlay. but the setup of the overlay network is through existing ML2 and its underlying Overlay mechanism driver which is out of scope of this project. The SFC functionality added by this project is built on top of existing Neutron supported transport mechanism. If new Overlay or other transport mechanisms need to be added, it should be added in a separate project.  

2) The Chain API parameter allows the user to specify what SFC encap mechanism to use for the chain, whether it is NSH or VLAN or none. The data plane components will be programmed to use that encap according to the IETF standard. 

3) Agree with you that SG is limited to ACL and not good for expressing a more flex policy? There have been such comments before and also in IRC meeting discussion. The consensus is to create a separate new and modular flow classifier. 

4) Dynamic change of the SFC graph by an SF will be achieved through data path "bypass bit" notification from the SF to SFF (as proposed in IETF draft) or through SFF detecting a failed SF and re-do local load balancing. Due to its dynamics, it makes more sense to implement this  between the data path components. If Admin wants to update the SFC graph path, it can do this via the update chain API. 

5) Metadata can be passed inband through IETF service chain header encap mechanism. If the data path SFF supports the IETF service chain header format, it will be able to handle the metadata.   

6) The API allows the user to create two or more service chain paths that cross at a SF point, i.e. the forks you requires. We will not use security group, so your concern on SG is not there.'}, {'account_id': 11907, 'date': '2015-06-30 21:25:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Here are my replies to Meni's comments: 

1) The policy configuration and life cycle management of SF are outside of this project scope. This is in compliant with the consensus reached in ONF Openflow standard organization and compliant with its service chain architecture spec. SFC will only deal with how to specify the chain and how to realize the chaining. Each SF is treated in a generic way as a node with Neutron ports. But   w.r.t. synchronizing the encap format between the data path components, the API allows the user to specify the encap mechanism in the "parameter" of the API. Please refer to the latest spec for detail info. 

2) Current API allows both a pair of ports and a single port. For a chain which has single-port SF, the direction of the chain path can be derived through the SFF's previous hop source address. It seems no need for a direction flag.  Also if we want a direction flag, that flag needs to first be added in the IETF service chain header encapsulation spec. 

3) The API already allows specification of an encapsulation format defined per chain.

4) Yes, we can extend the "parameter" in the API to cover   the "failure policy" specification.'}, {'account_id': 11907, 'date': '2015-07-01 00:36:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-01 00:38:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

Hi Nicolas, the parameters in the flow classifier can always be easily extended to include more flow descriptor parameters. Future extension can include user defined flow descriptor parameters as well as new L4~L7 parameters. For the first release, we would like to concentrate on delivering the base service chain functionality. I remember you mentioned adding a L7 application ID to the flow descriptor parameter. My question is: Is the application ID embedded in the original raw flow packets or is it an ID generated by the DPI service function? If it is the former case, then yes it can be added to the flow descriptor parameter. If it is the latter case, then it should be added as a metadata of the chain instead of a flow descriptor parameter. What do you think?'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-07-06 20:37:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
NetApp: E-Series fix deletion of missing volume

When a Cinder volume is deleted but the backend volume is missing,
an exception was being thrown, rather than swallowed and being logged.
A KeyError was being expected, but a VolumeNotFound exception was
actually being raised.

This patch catches the VolumeNotFound exception, and logs a debug
message if the volume could not be deleted from the backend (because
it no longer exists). This patch restores compatibility with older
versions where an exception would not be thrown.

Closes-Bug: 1502166
Change-Id: I47a8d9b408fc4ac7fae30f043b0dfca0bb763d8d

commit_message:
Deprecate version.yaml

At the moment feature_groups are defined during
ISO build in version.yaml file. We need to avoid
using build time defined parameters because
we are moving to the package based delivery approach.

Depends-On: I05e841d4279bc61645cefb68f411a93b67e57189
Related-Bug: #1513737
Related-Bug: #1515517
Change-Id: I4f96fec73f991094bca65de5f1d1014662fbb2b4

commit_message:
Deprecate heat-keystone-setup

Keystone shell is deprecated in this release, use openstack client
in heat-keystone-setup. And add a deprecation warning to this
script.

Change-Id: I11334f0c8b035723a11f42bcfea054fc358a3e9f
Closes-Bug: #1460884

commit_message:
raise minimum for pysnmp

there was an api change between 4.2.1 and 4.3 which changes the
format of method response. we can support both in ceilometer
but it's probably best to just raise the minimum anyways.

Change-Id: Ia45e818c9f12fe6bf3e48e09b22e187fe7f33092
Related-Bug: #1504588
Depends-On: I7167692e856da871ce0edad38cdd8c0deed46fb4

commit_message:
Fix issues in Glance filesystem backend

The drop root change for Glance highlighted the fact that we were
binding volumes from glance_data into the wrong container - it was
glance_registry whereas it should be glance_api. This would result in
all images being lost if the glance_api container happens to restart.

Also, we need a sudoers file to chown the file backend dir to the glance
user.

Change-Id: If04337045bb94b3126e48d1f5bf0ea29e20373ae
Closes-Bug: #1516729

"}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-02-27 16:54:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

I am really not a fan of the Context resource; it's another hack of the kind discussed in the heat-exorcism session at the Icehouse summit. Don't think of a resource as 'a place to stick some data'. Think of it as 'a step in a workflow' and as 'a thing behind an API that is identified with a UUID'. This is neither of those.

A couple of other possible implementations come to mind. The first is a special section in the environment for defining contexts... possibly with a custom function to retrieve them.

Alternatively (and this is preferable IMHO if it works the way I think it does), just have the context data passed directly as a property to the OS::Heat::Stack and encourage the user to use the new get_file built-in function to retrieve it from a separate file if they want to re-use it in multiple places."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-03-07 06:03:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Qiming, regarding the disable_rollback I was actually not sure whether we should really use the same setting from the parent stack.

After a second thought, it might be that your original implementation of setting disable_rollback to True might be correct. That is, we may not want the remote stack to automatically roll back, but rollback is triggered by the parent stack. I.e. when the parent stack does rollback, it would call delete() on the remote stack resource explicitly. If the remote stack had already rolled itself back, this might be a problem.

Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-12-10 12:24:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 41: Verified+1

Wow, fantastic work y'all!

I can imagine circumstances where the user would want to control disable_rollback (not so much on create, where it just slows everything down, but on update) so in the long run I think we'll want to add that as a property (or an update policy?).

For now, I think True is the correct default on create. For update it would be slightly better to use self.stack.disable_rollback since that will mean that the child stack will restore any still-extant replaced resources, rather than going ahead and deleting them before reporting the failure."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2014-12-10 20:53:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 41: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Adds multi-region support for stack resource

Adds new resource type called OS::Heat::Stack which allows
creating new stack in specified region using heatclient.

Implements: blueprint multi-region-support

Co-Authored-By: Qiming Teng <tengqim@cn.ibm.com>

Change-Id: I62cb07877702c57dd0e77dbcb0e123a3ec2c885d

commit_message:
Fix an issue with handling invalid section names

Invalid section names in the TOSCA template could cause an
unexpected exception that is due to not handling an error properly.
This patch is to fix the issue and add a proper unit test to
verify the fix.

Change-Id: Icbf7c3d0c8a26d8d09c19c68bd58154d4da9cd43
Closes-Bug: #1516826

commit_message:
Fix the missing help descripiton of "image-create"

Now, when use "glance help" to show the help message, the description
of 'image-create' is missing.

Change-Id: I748209222c540e0024580dccac850ea465d176b4
Closes-bug: #1510340
(cherry picked from commit dfcb468c1da3513d18da39969ef55bd22bc6685b)

Now VLAN IDs cannot be equal within any particular NIC (or bond)

This new validation covers the case when network template is not in use.
It will be separate patchset where network templates are covered.

commit_message:
Allow VLAN IDs intersection

Remove old validation of VLAN IDs intersection and add new one.
Now VLAN IDs cannot be equal within any particular NIC (or bond)
but they can be equal for different networks in general.
This new validation covers the case when network template is not in use.

Partial-Bug: #1473047

Change-Id: I27a8326edc00acc6b95ee51fce203527e82e47d7
Blueprint: nodegroups-share-network-parameters

commit_message:
Change event emitted on signal failure

If a signal fails, the event should be SIGNAL_FAILED, indicating
the correct nature of the event.

Change-Id: I39d0160c70ba3adb716c58aa45458f2f13377428
Closes-Bug: #1516681
Implements: partial blueprint resource-notifications

commit_message:
Support download from and upload to Cinder volumes

Currently Glance's Cinder backend driver doesn't support
uploading, downloading, and deletion.

As missing parts in Cinder listed in
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/glance/+spec/glance-cinder-driver
(os-brick library, readonly-volumes, multi-attach) are now supported,
now we can implement uploading and downloading for it.

Change-Id: Ic548289c3bf195abde28a5cf52944632b926b487

commit_message:
Use trusts for post image upload registry call

Prevent failure of setting an image to the 'active' status after
image upload due to an expired user token.

Co-Authored-By: Mike Fedosin <mfedosin@mirantis.com>

Implements bp trust-authentication
Change-Id: I407bac84750b2e26bacd59d21dd72289209bf955

commit_message:
Fix help line when subcommand is not passed

When subcommands are not passed to `glance help` the compatibility help
line at the bottom shows `None`.

Change-Id: Icbce0728a77443ade1f694d119dcc8cb2d7d8aad
Closes-bug: #1517156

commit_message:
adding general packaging information

This document is intended for horizon developers, adding
background on packaging topics. It even might be useful
for distribution packagers.

A few distributions are mentioned here, the list is neither complete
nor has been selected on purpose in that way.

Co-Authored-By: Thomas Goirand <thomas@goirand.fr>
Co-Authored-By: Andreas Jaeger <aj@suse.com>
Change-Id: If771636a086c384748f4cf34847d0a7a84a590ac

commit_message:
Remove refresh in Stack update_and_save

We uselessly refresh the stack object when we save it, as we don't use
the result anywhere. Let's remove that useless query.

Change-Id: Idbc737a0d88aa98e69979f6edd88b8b148030388
