[{'account_id': 18086, 'date': '2015-11-17 09:16:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-11-17 09:16:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Fix wrong type of exception raised

generate_template and resource_schema methods of service.py
raises wrong type of exceptions after catching them.

Also resource validation failure should not raise stack
validation exception.

Change-Id: I44b8d37db7d2687cee2a7b675dd062b3af3ee167
Closes-Bug: #1447194
(cherry-picked from 9a4d719ea1a6ca63f527b5c78308fd288058d42b)

commit_message:
Log an error on an uncaught exception in a thread

Exceptions in synchronous tasks get caught by the olso_messaging code but
for asynchronous tasks run in threads with nothing wait()ing for them,
there is no top level error handling, and hence no logging. (Tracebacks
would be written to stderr, so systemd users would see them only in the
journal rather than heat-engine.log, and other users would quite likely
lose them altogether.) This change ensures that any uncaught exceptions are
logged as errors.

Change-Id: I9410aa7ffd83391ea4db13c6e8cf49f26d3049fb
Closes-Bug: #1492427
(cherry picked from commit 03d9aebbc7d5fba048fa9f39813704e70dee9c5d)

commit_message:
Log an error on an uncaught exception in a thread

Exceptions in synchronous tasks get caught by the olso_messaging code but
for asynchronous tasks run in threads with nothing wait()ing for them,
there is no top level error handling, and hence no logging. (Tracebacks
would be written to stderr, so systemd users would see them only in the
journal rather than heat-engine.log, and other users would quite likely
lose them altogether.) This change ensures that any uncaught exceptions are
logged as errors.

Change-Id: I9410aa7ffd83391ea4db13c6e8cf49f26d3049fb
Closes-Bug: #1492427
(cherry picked from commit 03d9aebbc7d5fba048fa9f39813704e70dee9c5d)

[{'created': '2015-10-27 03:03:26.000000000', 'message': "Remove version hardcoding for 'detail' method

This patch actually uses the _determine_current_version method
to determine the CURRENT glance version in use. This patchset is

commit_message:
Remove version hardcoding for 'detail' method

This patch actually uses the _determine_current_version method
to determine the CURRENT glance version in use. This patchset is
kept small for the ease of review. It takes the approach of making
the version information optional while initializing the glance client
This gives us a way to incrementally remove the version hard coding
from various CRUD operations - one at a time. In this patchset,
an experiment is performed with the 'detail' method.

Should all of these go well, an attempt will be made to address
the compatibility issues between v1 and v2 in further patchsets.

Related to blueprint use-glance-v2-api

Change-Id: Ied4d8f99f1784224af5c4f903f87bb332c284b1a
Co-Authored-By: Mike Fedosin <mfedosin@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fix Nova's indirection fixture override

This mirrors the indirection fixture override that we have for
object_class_action() while we transition fully to the base
VersionedObjectRegistry. This prevents us from breaking with current
oslo.versionedobjects.

This also caused a few other tests to get run with manifest calls,
which needed to be converted to continue to work.

Change-Id: I2aaa42784b2cc5c6898a3fac0c951dd57dd4f4c6
Closes-Bug: #1516805

in test-requirements.txt to make sure it can updated by global
automatically.

commit_message:
Fix problem with type mismatch on Kafka config

Fix type mismatch on partitions config parameter in Kafka
config. Currently only supports one partition. In the future
could remove this altogether or add support for multiple
partitions. This became an issue because oslo.config was
updated and began detecting this error.

Change-Id: Ia17e2e70030c9dd22e93e6901dcd1d3db040d971

commit_message:
propose new tempest layer4 job

This runs all the heat / sahara / trove tests in one test run which
ensures they all work for tempest changes. It will also allow us to
gate decouple these projects from neutron / nova / etc because we can
remove the specific heat / sahara / trove jobs from tempest if this is
voting.

Change-Id: I82f0a415f2284e1c053117b1c2e98b6b55c048de

commit_message:
Disable no-shadow

http://eslint.org/docs/rules/no-shadow

Consensus seems to be against this. See comments on review for
relevant discussion.

This rules prevents the redeclaration of variables in inherited scopes.
While technically there's nothing wrong with using a variable with
the same name in such a context, it does make the following lines
of code a bit more confusing, as it's not always apparent (especially
with deep nesting) which of the two scoped variables is being accessed.

Change-Id: Ic4a04c4496a382ac935ab470d439089739c1e928

function foo(optional_param) {

I agree that the above is a good point, but yet I would maintain that ensuring that parameters are not reassigned is a good idea, especially when working in teams as large as that within OpenStack.

commit_message:
Added and enabled gates for ruby fuel repos

To continue work on integration of Fuel-* projects in
OpenStack infrastructure.

* Following gates are added and enabled by this commit:
- gate-fuel-astute-rake-dsvm
- gate-fuel-nailgun-agent-rake-dsvm

Change-Id: Ic00180899bb9bf3cc1e8b13c65c9f930f813f6db

commit_message:
Add rake-dsvm gate job-template

To continue work on integration of Fuel-* projects in
OpenStack infrastructure.

We have two ruby component in Fuel: fuel-astute and
fuel-nailgun-agent. We use rspec for unit tests.
We can not use gate-{name}-rake which use trusty and ruby 1.9
because our gem deps require ruby 2.0
We can use puppet-unit jobs on devstack with centos7
but it looks useless to install puppet before running rspec.

So we offer to make the ruby unit test job on centos7.

This patch creates a basic ruby unit test job
which setups bundle and runs rake spec on dsvm

Change-Id: I13991cd5c145bf968069f4b7ac706c9ffecb953b

commit_message:
Only send ironic bootloader info if its supported

We introduced a backwards incompat change in
I9c1d8643be7cb9e273d65ddd791715a5c271fd93 because we do not check if
this feature is supported.

Change-Id: Ieae6d2c89cc1e91905ac51d97117c2e220157525
Related-Bug: #1441556

commit_message:
Pass ceph::pool arguments when calling class

Pass the ceph::pool properties as arguments to the class call
instead of setting them as class defaults.

Ceph recommends max 32 PGs and min 4 PGs per OSD so this change
also lowers the defaults to 32 which works with 1 OSD, suits well
a scenario with 3 OSDs and is easy to customize in the static
hiera if more than 8 OSDs are deployed.

More info at: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1252546

Change-Id: Ifed11d1857900b2251dfdf69d6b6f168150e6330

commit_message:
Enable quote-props "as-needed"

This rule aims to enforce use of quotes in property names, only
in cases where they are strictly required (such as +/- in the name).
In all other cases, it will point out unecessary quotes.

http://eslint.org/docs/rules/quote-props

Change-Id: I7925329a3291ddb836ba9d971bdab529848596de

commit_message:
Delete python bytecode before every test run

Because python creates pyc files during tox runs, certain
changes in the tree, like deletes of files, or switching
branches, can create spurious errors.

Change-Id: I77f144fc681eadcf8fd7fe735753090e3ebc6084
Closes-Bug: #1368661

commit_message:
Cleaning up node visitor

The context object in node visitor was being copied from a template.
However, most fields were irrelevant to most tests. This has now
been stripped out. The imports and import_alias fields are preserved
as they were the only fields that were not repopulated before the
test set call.

Change-Id: Ib8871586e3a98acbffb2cc1a67085bfd4d5d417a

This improves node visitor code to use half the recursive depth that
it was previously using. This fixes bug #1498261 as we no longer
explode with a recursion depth error.

Additionally, this adds a generic testing path for any AST type. We
can now write tests that will be run against any node type by name.
A few existing node visit methods were simply replicating the now
generic code path and have thus been removed.

Change-Id: Idc77a5f50dfab3988243ce32d3de5c61c85b0b72
Closes-bug: 1498261
'}]
commit_message:
Improving node visitor

This improves node visitor code to use half the recursive depth that
it was previously using. This fixes bug #1498261 as we no longer
explode with a recursion depth error.

Additionally, this adds a generic testing path for any AST type. We
can now write tests that will be run against any node type by name.
A few existing node visit methods were simply replicating the now
generic code path and have thus been removed.

Change-Id: Idc77a5f50dfab3988243ce32d3de5c61c85b0b72
Closes-bug: 1498261

commit_message:
Node Network Groups support on Networks tab

This change adds support of node network group in Fuel UI.
It is possible to view, rename and delete them now.

Known issues:
- gateways not set in multi-rack
- it's impossible to save networks configuration
  change in multirack due to unsupported shared
  networks in nailgun
- showAll state should save in db (ui_settings model)
- strange animation in navigation tab on node group
  renaming

Related to blueprint multirack-in-fuel-ui

Change-Id: I413f77ce1dca59ae2c48ba743513ddf5584713e8

Sync sslutils to ironic-api for support HTTPS

oslo-incubator.openstack.common.sslutils have some code support
SSL, Ironic Api support HTTPS can use it.

Closes-bug: #1430213

commit_message:
Switched StrOpt to ListOpt in CORS allowed_origins

This patch switches the 'allowed_origin' CORS configuration option
from a single string to an array of strings. This will let you
configure multiple domains simultaneously with the same options,
without having to add additional configuration blocks.

By doing this, pastedeploy users will no longer have to configure
mulitple filters if they wish to grant access to more than one
domain.

Change-Id: Ie2e57b76717604f701daa16ebf8ffa8c06835e3c

commit_message:
Enable latent CORS configuration via pastedeploy

In the case where paste deployment and oslo are used in concert,
it is not possible for an application to easily ship required
configuraton properties, such as custom headers, with their
release artifact. This patch adds parameters which expose
set_latent to paste.ini users, permitting the above.

Tests and documentation have been updated.

commit_message:
allow to set clean_nodes option

 On test environment, when working with real HW nodes,
 it is usefull to disable celaning in order to speed-up
 node-deletion process.

Change-Id: I3aaa27b25ef276da6920a1c0510b80f7d965ebd2

commit_message:
allow to configure Q_L3_METADATA_PORT

 User images built with disk-image-builder use 80 port to obtain
 metadata. Option Q_L3_METADATA_PORT allows to configure metadata
 port on devstack environment.

Change-Id: I97e50c5527f64fabcb4e5640b6021d2d540451df

commit_message:
Ignore this please

Add retries to delete a volume in the RBD driver

This patch adds retries to delete a volume. After N tries of a
volume deletion failed we raise VolumeIsBusy exception.

Change-Id: I88b764624e81d70ec93511d618c4b1b6ba4556fc

commit_message:
Use os_package_type for libvirt service name

This change updates the puppet-nova module to use the correct libvirt
service name and log group for the debian packages. In addition the
tests have been updated to properly test the debian and ubuntu
packages.

Change-Id: I8fcca7c1d14f5dec3840789ef00c9ccd11c6191b
Closes-Bug: #1515076

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables
* Remove requirements.txt from deps, as this is
  already added automatically


Change-Id: I49d14fc878521e2b6fd4bd13dfd12f99a245b1fd

commit_message:
Stop using IIFE for index.js

`index.js` is a NodeJS file. NodeJS automatically adds IIFE around
JS code from each NodeJS file and passes in some variables like
`module` object.  Therefore it is redundant to have IIFE in
`index.js`.

Change-Id: Iea8ad83d8f3598aa506063614db482eeef52db4e

Given the variable name is *the* reason causing the percentage bug to happen, I'd argue that it is important to be in this commit or in another one normalizing these names.

Another reason not to do this slowly is that future developers won't know what the correct way to go is, potentially allowing the problem to persist or even increase.

In any case, I'd still argue against having a bunch of renames in a patch that's actually doing something else. commit_message:
Add sort options to columns in job detail page

Now we are able to sort for each one of the table fields as well as
search for specific tests.

Change-Id: I3e862d8a133e9733aebef23ece5a94c1685dc45e

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables
* Remove requirements.txt from deps, as this is
  already added automatically
* sitepackages : default is already false


Change-Id: Ie2f14094bb896227021f3d0bb81f721032a0c531

commit_message:
Increse timeout in 'prepare_ha_ceph_neutron' test

Add 20 minutes to the deployment timeout in
'prepare_ha_ceph_neutron' test, because deployment
of nodes with few roles takes more time.

Change-Id: I3bb67c0e86284b8e59d00c8868baa17c06f42191
Closes-bug: #1517071

Please add a spec test for this case'}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2015-11-12 22:48:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I would but this is a workaround for data returned magically by another provider so I'm kinda out of my element on this one. What's the best way to mock out the keystone tenant lookup here?"}, {'account_id': 9983, 'date': '2015-11-12 23:05:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yeah, there's no spec test for self.get_tenant_id at all :P

How about this, to future proof somewhat::

    def self.get_tenant_id(catalog, name, domain='Default')
      instance_type = 'keystone_tenant'
      instance = catalog.resource("#{instance_type.capitalize!}[#{name}]")
      if ! instance
        instance = Puppet::Type.type(instance_type).instances.find do |i|
          # We need to check against the domain name because of
          # https://review.openstack.org/#/c/226919/ which changed the naming
          # format for the tenant to include ::<Domain name>.
          # TODO(aschultz): remove ="Default" as part of M-cycle - make domain mandatory
        i.provider.name == name || i.provider.name == "#{name}::#{domain}"'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-12 23:24:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add workaround for v2 tenant names

The change (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/226919/) to the naming
convention for keystone tenants has introduced an issue with some
neutron providers as they are no longer able to find the v2 named
tenants since the name returned from the keystone provider now
also includes the domain. This change adds a check to see if the name
matches the Default domain applied by default until support for a
resource without the domain set is removed.

Change-Id: I4c5b6b2b663a1d08005369fa755ac03b0603102b
Closes-Bug: #1515787

commit_message:
Support of PyMySQL driver for MySQL backend

Add ability to use python-pymysql library
as backend for MySQL connections.
Switch acceptance tests on pyMySQL usage.
Docs: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/PyMySQL_evaluation

Change-Id: I52447482f15a1c075566c7596ce7c5465446fb5a

commit_message:
Remove protocol-port option from Create Pool

The current API reference document states that protocol-port can
be assigned when a new LBaaS V2 pool is created. However, this
is not correct.
The following patch fixes the same.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1516781

Change-Id: I3126e949541ee3be7a613333d50a80a9d375d74a

commit_message:
Kilo backport

Service_provider in neutron.conf
	In kilo it is not possible to add service
	provider config. Thats why the configuration has
	to be set in neutron.conf

Add namespace to extension
	In kilo an extension for neutron still
	needs a get_namespace method.

Hack around neutrons fixed plugin rules
	The list of allowed services is fixed in kilo.
	This commit adds BGPVPN to the allowed services.

Align requirements to kilo

Deliver bgpvpn_id through network_association dict
	In kilo the parent_id can not be transported
	thats way the bgpvpn_id is included in the
	network_association.

	in neutronclient/v2_0/client.py:
    def extend_create(self, resource_singular, path):
            def _fx(body=None):
	                return self.create_ext(path, body)
			        setattr(self, "create_%s" %
				resource_singular, _fx)

Align unittests to kilo
	bgpvpn_id is given in kwargs not in args.

Change-Id: Ie2043c5d6fe70a53e295c12aba724db49ad157db

commit_message:
[WIP] [manner 2] lb: separate agent loop from linuxbridge specific code

made agent_type constructor arg
move out RPC consumer topics to mgr class
Callbacks will be retrieved from mgr class
Manager is now passed as argument into agent
agent is not aware of interface or bridgemappings anymore
moved remove_port_binding to linuxbridgemanager class
renamed get_tap* to get_*
Move agent_state confiugrations to BridgeManager class
Move calculation of agent_id to BridgeManager class
rename br_mgr to mgr

Change-Id: I21e0a6b7bbb558384b13f8cb0ff515133d0b8970

(2 comments)

I started reviewing this, but gave up. This is clearly a valiant effort, but it's huge. I feel confident you should be able to cut this patch up into a lot of smaller pieces that are easier to review. Because of the sheer size, it's really hard to validate everything.

There is a dict mixin class in the library that lets you retain some dict-like behaviors on objects, like foo[attr] access, iteritems(), .update(dict), etc. Is there any reason not to break this up into smaller pieces that can land quickly on their own after a small amount of inspection?

I would recommend steps like this:

 1. Add the mixin to the volume object
 2. Do any pre-cleanups of very dicty behavior in existing code to prepare
 3. Start using the new volume object in the core
 4. Iterate through small localized changes to convert from dict to object syntax
 5. Remove the dict mixin to cleanup

Otherwise I think review of this patch will be really difficult. I dunno what the Cinder culture is here, but being familiar with the object stuff as I am, I find it too big to digest...

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 8247, 'date': '2015-09-30 17:59:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 96:

@Dan: We do have the mixin class in the volume object (base.CinderObjectDictCompat).  I could make this change simpler by not making changes against the dict to use object dot notation, but since there is no logic change to use dot notation, it was done in the same patch.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-10-01 13:41:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 96: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-10-01 13:42:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 96: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 15764, 'date': '2015-10-07 12:30:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 96:

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-10-12 18:17:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 99: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

I still think this is an amazingly large amount of change to make in a single patch. What happens if you land this, then a few more on top, and then realize that it's breaking something? It'll be impossible to bisect it down to a single change in this patch in a reasonable amount of time, which means you'll have to revert the whole thing, which will almost certainly not be clean.

Smaller changes that build up compatibility, make changes and then drop the setup are definitely good for making sure you can resolve issues, IMHO. So, because of the size, I haven't really reviewed the rest of this, but there are definitely plenty of seams on which to split this up.

I also think you should start making your RPC interfaces compatible as part of this work. If you don't, you're going to have spread this object stuff everywhere and still not be able to do upgrades just because of the core RPC problems."}, {'account_id': 11600, 'date': '2015-10-13 10:18:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 99: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

We've run into problems when trying to split this patch further, if I recall correctly it was difficult to split get, create, update and delete without actually changing and adding more code.

I agree on the RPC compatibility remarks, but that's something we as Cinder community haven't design yet. We'll probably base our implementation on how Nova's doing it but this may be agreed in Tokio. From my perspective this patch is good to go once rebased and we'll continue with doing smaller changes with single RPC methods *and* start making our RPC API compatible between Liberty and Mitaka."}, {'account_id': 8247, 'date': '2015-10-20 03:02:58.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 100.'}, {'account_id': 8247, 'date': '2015-10-20 03:06:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 100:

'}, {'created': '2015-06-09 14:10:45.000000000', 'message': 'Conversion to volume object

Switch cinder internals to use volume
oslo_versionedobject.  This patch switches cinder
internals to use volume oslo_versionedobjects for
get, create, and delete volume APIs.

There are db.volume_get, db.volume_update, and
db.volume_destroy calls still left in the cinder
code base that need to be switched over to
oslo_versionedobjects, but these calls are in other
volume APIs, e.g. retype.  Changing them in this
patch would make this patch even larger and harder
to review.  Further work is required to remove the
rest of db.volume_* calls and update other volume
APIs, which is left as follow-up patches.

Change-Id: Ifb36726f8372e21d1d9825d6ab04a072e5db4a6a
Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-objects

patch would make this patch even larger and harder
to review.  Further work is required to remove the
rest of db.volume_* calls and update other volume
APIs, which is left as follow-up patches.

The following patch updates get_volume and delete_volume
API to use volume versionedobjects.  It only includes
changes to the core cinder code.  Changes in the drivers
are left to each driver maintainer to update.

Note that this patch DOES NOT try to use
object dot notation everywhere, since it would
increase the size of the patch.  Instead, it
will be done in subsequent patches.

includes changes to the core cinder code.  Changes in the
drivers are left to each driver maintainer to update.

object dot notation everywhere, since it would
increase the size of the patch.  Instead, it
will be done in subsequent patches.

commit_message:
Update get/delete_volume API to use versionedobjects

The following patch updates get_volume and delete_volume
API to use volume versionedobjects.  Changes were made to
be backwards compatible with older RPC clients. It only
includes changes to the core cinder code.  Changes in the
drivers are left to each driver maintainer to update.

Note that this patch DOES NOT try to use
object dot notation everywhere, since it would
increase the size of the patch.  Instead, it
will be done in subsequent patches.

Co-Authored-By: Michal Dulko <michal.dulko@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Szymon Wroblewski <szymon.wroblewski@intel.com>
Change-Id: Ifb36726f8372e21d1d9825d6ab04a072e5db4a6a
Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-objects

commit_message:
Fix stack lock ActionInProgress in the admin case

When the engine starts and tries to reset the status of stacks in
progress, it tries to acquire the stack lock on them. The stack lock
queries the database to retrieve the name of the stack, but does a
tenant-scope query, thus fails when as we use the admin context during
startup. This fixes it by passing tenant_safe=False.

Change-Id: I4393fdb601eedb36d7288afd57fb5a1c96af7216
Closes-Bug: #1516712

commit_message:
Symlink ceph libraries out of venv

Currently, we install python-rados and python-rbd via apt when ceph
integration is enabled, which causes issues when venvs are used in the
environment.  This commit adds a temporary work-around by creating
symlinks in the venv to the installed libraries outside.

There is currently a ceph issue [1] in progress to make this possible,
and once this has been completed we can update ceph_client role to
install python packages instead.

[1] http://tracker.ceph.com/issues/5900

Change-Id: Ia7a3ceae002054fd75e0305892b20ce1143f8dcc
Closes-Bug: #1509837
(cherry picked from commit a0ab6f7a6efea1dabf5ac006f766c17596a0d10b)

in keystone.

commit_message:
Add support for enabling L2 population in Neutron

This change adds support for enabling/disabling L2 population in
Neutron agents. It currently defaults to false.

Change-Id: I3dd19feb4acb1046bc560b35e5a7a111364ea0d7

in neutronclient/v2_0/client.py
    def extend_create(self, resource_singular, path):
            def _fx(body=None):
	                return self.create_ext(path, body)
			        setattr(self, "create_%s" %
				resource_singular, _fx)
_fx does only take 1 argument.

Change-Id: I161f3336c88911d61870df9c5fffa278592ddc7a
'}]
commit_message:
KILO: Deliver bgpvpn_id through network_association dict

In kilo the parent_id can not be transported
thats way the bgpvpn_id is included in the network_association.

in neutronclient/v2_0/client.py
    def extend_create(self, resource_singular, path):
            def _fx(body=None):
	                return self.create_ext(path, body)
			        setattr(self, "create_%s" %
				resource_singular, _fx)
_fx does only take 1 argument.

Change-Id: I161f3336c88911d61870df9c5fffa278592ddc7a

commit_message:
Fix default device_driver entry in lbaas_agent.ini

Due to the repository splitting the new location should be used
and the old one is only for Juno and older.

Change-Id: I47347818a742805b7da8a18c66bfa6703d10da9a
Closes-Bug: #1507314
(cherry picked from commit c72f8a078e76004b92a8c23b493b45e5ec527827)

commit_message:
KILO: Service_provider in neutron.conf

In kilo it is not possible to add service
provider config. Thats why the configuration has
to be set in neutron.conf

Change-Id: I07858ac1f4ba3598c1b10cda3e6a653f7fc6496c

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-28 13:28:04.000000000', 'message': 'Add stability rabbit test

Add stability tests with next scenario:
* Get rabbit master
* move it to other node
* delete contraint for rabbit resource
* Run OSTF
* get new rabbit master
* destroy it
* run OSTF
* power on destroyed node
* run OSTF
* repeat failover cases COUNT_REPEAT times,

By defaut COUNT_REPEAT is 2
Closes-Bug: #1458830

Change-Id: I6fb8d540e930c4d46ef73913e442100424e05047

commit_message:
Add stability rabbit test

Add stability tests with next scenario:
* Get rabbit master
* move it to other node
* delete contraint for rabbit resource
* Run OSTF
* get new rabbit master
* destroy it
* run OSTF
* power on destroyed node
* run OSTF
* repeat failover cases COUNT_REPEAT times,

By defaut COUNT_REPEAT is 2
Closes-Bug: #1458830

Change-Id: I6fb8d540e930c4d46ef73913e442100424e05047

commit_message:
Exclude old Shibboleth options from docs

The documentation for setting up Shibboleth gives you a snippet of code
that you can copy and paste and then later in notes tells you to remove
options for apache 2.4.

At this point apache 2.4 should be considered the default and not the
exception and we can easily convey this information in the config
snippet and make copying it easier than having to re-read documentation
to figure out why options are unknown.

Change-Id: I9546b6b9cabdaffdb0473711dc07fc234f00d297

commit_message:
Enable pkcs11-key-generation command

Allows pkcs11-key-generation command to work. It was not moved to
barbican.cmd properly(naming was off). I also made it a .py file
as it should be so that it conforms to pep8. Documentation fixes
are submitted as well.

Change-Id: I5994547040f7d3182ffcaf34f2fe995395fb055f
Closes-Bug: #1515424

@Dan: I think some of your comments assume that we support some type of rpc compatibility in cinder.  I could be wrong, but I do not think we do have it.  Hence, some of my changes are as such.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-09-30 18:09:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)

Thang, yeah, it's clear that cinder doesn't yet practice that behavior. However, the whole goal of this work is make upgrades a reality, right? The RPC stuff takes time to fix, both technically and culture shifts. Things don't get better until a cycle after you've made that change. Given the goal of this work, I would say it's a good place to start doing the right thing. The more you do right now, the less needs fixing later.

One could make the argument that the objects stuff itself isn't worth doing at all if you're not already doing the RPC bit right, or at least on the way down that road!"}, {'account_id': 8247, 'date': '2015-09-30 18:23:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Update retype API to use versionedobjects

The following patch updates retype API to use volume
versionedobjects.  Changes were made to be backwards
compatible with older RPC clients.  It only includes
changes to the core cinder code.  Changes in the
drivers are left to each driver maintainer to update.

Note that this patch DOES NOT try to use object dot
notation everywhere, since it would increase the
size of the patch.  Instead, it will be done in
subsequent patches.

Change-Id: Ie79abf085349b496930fb75a76f299e65587ba6d
Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-objects

commit_message:
fix os-instance_usage_audit_log name

os-instance-usage-audit-log is not a resource, it's actually
os-instance_usage_audit_log. Why is kind of unclear, but that's what
we've got at this point.

We should fix the docs to be accurate to the code.

Change-Id: Ie9d60990c44d9571b87fe9403a3860be682ef929
Closes-Bug: #1516158

commit_message:
Use flat_networks=* default for the ml2 plugin

We are setting our flat_networks setting for the ml2 plugin
manually to '' which as of neutron git commit
cb712c5a9ee2717f5d34b00a420529b842db90c7 causes a
'Flat networks are disabled' error to occur when
we attempt to create the ctlplane network.

This patch drops the configurion of flat_networks from
instack and instead relies on the puppet-neutron default
of '*' which will work.

Change-Id: I880c9a159a46d9a288cb1f8bf79af30e5045d5ab
Closes-bug: #1515315

commit_message:
Include Babel polyfill

We now use ES6 and Babel relies on ES6 features, so polyfill is
required now.

Change-Id: I84be932f3292d66c581cea181e167fd65d1a3019
Closes-Bug: #1516987

commit_message:
Support partial upgrades of Neutron in DVR mode.

When Neutron is running in DVR mode, we need to leave both the L2 and
L3 agents running.  This patch takes advantage of new support in
DevStack that allows separate control of the L3 agent.

Change-Id: I9bc9fdc233114411f78276b3abc1ca8cf33ef52e
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>
Depends-on: I392a84790d4282edc52edd16502907dfeaefd41e

commit_message:
Support partial Neutron upgrades.

We test nova without upgrading nova-compute to cover the rolling
compute node upgrade scenario.  To test the same scenario for a
deployment that includes Neutron, we need to be able to upgrade
everything except the Neutron L2 agent.

Change-Id: Id8e8985eb51813a07843a87ce114f3d68a98194e
Depends-on: I7eb87fba778aff3e4514813c6232dafa99ee2912
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

subject: Separate start/stop control of the Neutron L3 agent.

commit_message:
Separate start/stop control of the Neutron L3 agent.

This patch is in support of adding rolling compute node upgrade
testing with Neutron enabled.  In the case of running Neutron in DVR
mode, compute nodes will also be running the L3 agent, so we need to
be able to control that agent separately, as well.

Change-Id: I392a84790d4282edc52edd16502907dfeaefd41e
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
neutron: Stop using deprecated option name.

When q-svc starts, the log contains the following warning:

2015-09-04 19:38:13.282 WARNING oslo_config.cfg [-] Option "username"
from group "nova" is deprecated. Use option "user-name" from group
"nova".

This patch makes the recommended change so that devstack no longer
configures neutron with the deprecated option name.

Change-Id: I128946570d755e12346ec7b11fe8fc8c40a8611c
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Switch heat to use auth_uri and identity_uri

This change updates heat to use the auth_uri and identity_uri instead of
the deprecated keystone_host parameter.

Change-Id: Ie9ac86c17ceebb675b2053230668e17bdfb66f88
Closes-Bug: #1514983

commit_message:
Add 410 response description to ceilometer

If gnocchi is enabled, some API returns 410 response by gnocchi_abort().

Ref.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/202925/15/ceilometer/api/controllers/v2/root.py,unified

Change-Id: I5f9898ce3e59f7787b723e66ea8c1c812606b42b
Closes-Bug: #1477996

commit_message:
Add firstapp sec2&3 for fog

Adds section 2 and 3 for the fog SDK for FirstApp tutorial,
as well as fixes the repo that the faafo is cloned from
in section 1.

Co-Author: Caleb Boylan <calebboylan@gmail.com>
Co-Author: Tom Fifield <tom@openstack.org>

Partial-Bug: #1449329

Change-Id: I553af22e904261d3465eda4301a664d24fe91b31

commit_message:
Hyper-V: refactors utilsfactory

The Hyper-V API can change from a version to another (e.g. new
features), requiring a new Utils class to be added for specific
versions.

Refactors utilsfactory module. In this way, a new utils class
can be added without adding a new parameter when retrieving the
suitable class for windows version.

Change-Id: I1ea398473947a0d9afea08c08fea09dc09afea09

commit_message:
Move action status definition to consts module

This patch moves action status definition from db.sqlalchemy.api
module to consts module. This is a copy of the definition defined
in senlin.engine.actions.base module.

Change-Id: I0a79d4b46e9a529b5ee601103eb73650db2028fb

Remove verify_network_configuration method

to having advanced check 'check_ipconfig_for_template'
that is used in networking templates tests

commit_message:
Make libvirt migration security configurable

Adding flags to choose between tls/tcp connections as well as
sasl/none authentication when configuring libvirt migration.

This allows to deploy proper libvirt security in combination with
the nova::compute class.

Change-Id: Ib479a1f4cd2df0d55347ed71fb8f0ab69aaeceef

commit_message:
Add SSL support for Rally deployment

Set additional environment variable for HTTPS
proxy and enable insecure mode for SSL, because
in tests we use self-signed certificate.

Change-Id: Ia70fd71c65dc5a265b80e1d87da2d33f50d341c6
Closes-bug: #1516029

commit_message:
Bring corosync cluster to maintenance mode

To fix quorum loss tests should bring corosync cluster to maintenance mode
in following tests:
* ha_neutron_check_alive_rabbit
* ha_neutron_check_dead_rabbit
* ha_nova_check_alive_rabbit
* ha_nova_check_dead_rabbit

Change-Id: Ia185a12457d08e7ce7bba9d800a555f31e6e60c8
Closes-Bug: #1462942

commit_message:
Fix gate job for ostf repo

The thing is that nailgun tests require postgresql backend to
be available. So, we need to prepare it before running tests.
Fortunately, all unit tests are run on nodes where postgresql
is installed.

Change-Id: I8f93bb78cb4144f993fb55936e157b5fe153a4c1
Closes-Bug: #1516609

[{'created': '2015-10-22 10:56:13.000000000', 'message': 'Fix flake8 warnings

* Remove unused imports
* Add empty lines to respect the PEP8
* Sort imports
* Replace "timeout/10" with "timeout / 10" (add spaces)
* Fix style of comments
* Remove trailing spaces
* test_lockfile.py: add "# noqa" on the sqlite3 import, the import is
  used to decide if we skip the test or not
* tox.ini: enable all warnings except F841 (which will be fixed
  later)

Change-Id: I8218785f5cea23532357ec1756a3ab2255880d74
'}]
commit_message:
Fix flake8 warnings

* Remove unused imports
* Add empty lines to respect the PEP8
* Sort imports
* Replace "timeout/10" with "timeout / 10" (add spaces)
* Fix style of comments
* Remove trailing spaces
* test_lockfile.py: add "# noqa" on the sqlite3 import, the import is
  used to decide if we skip the test or not
* tox.ini: enable all warnings except F841 (which will be fixed
  later)

Change-Id: I8218785f5cea23532357ec1756a3ab2255880d74

commit_message:
Implements more smart retrying

This patch makes difference between messages which are sent
with retry=0 and retry!=0. In first case we consider that
request could be not idempotent and we should guarantee
that such messages we be not sent more then one time.
Therefore we use consuming without acknowledgements for such
messages and consuming with acknowledgements for messages which
could be processed twice to avoid message loses

Change-Id: I7dc1705e84dc6a7671bf1f379d4ef4980e41491e

Release Notes for version 1.2.0

1f1934e Add versions list function
bff356e Added reactivate/deactivate image using CLI
dfcb468 Fix the missing help descripiton of "image-create"
8a4cd79 Add documentation for running the functional tests
c7c0754 Updated from global requirements
d6a10f2 Remove unused sphinx Makefile
5a24705 Update docs to recommend KSA instead of KSC
84538d8 Use clouds.yaml from devstack for functional tests
4fb3092 Add translation to v2 shell
6b9133c Import i18n functions directly
8cf2bfc Updated from global requirements
b51634a improve readme contents
ca050ed Add support for setting Accept-Language header

36937bb Use the subcomand parsed args instead of the base
afd1810 Stop trying to send image_size to the server

a8a7c68 print usage when no argument is specified for python3

3d3d829 Fix human readable when size is None
19480df Add parsing the endpoint URL

commit_message:
Add release note publishing for OpenStack-Ansible

As per the release process changes for liberty and mitaka [1], the
release note publishing is being added to OpenStack-Ansible for the
purpose of implementing on-going release note additions.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/078301.html

commit_message:
Fix typo on quota limit error message

There is a typo on the error message that is shown when the user
tries to increase the user quota limit above the tenant quota
limit. This patch changes the error message from:

"Quota limit must less than %s."

to:

"Quota limit must be less than %s."

Change-Id: I826faf54ffeb7be647c76dde4bbd02db67c0c115
Closes-bug: #1516997

commit_message:
Make TripleO jobs run not only on master and remove noop-jobs

Until recently TripleO didn't maintain stable branches, but now we
do, so we need the gate jobs to work also on stable/liberty branches.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/240938/ aimed to enable this, but I
think this constraint is preventing the jobs running, e.g see:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/245670/

Also, after IRC discussion it was noted that we have a spurious
noop-jobs defined, where check jobs do exist, so remove this.

Change-Id: Ic5e6c442b4fd89776a3c18da75cd85438a52400c

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* sitepackages : default is already false


Change-Id: I12de2f2175fce3a0b24c16a1fc55100c2927883f

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables
* Remove requirements.txt from deps, as this is
  already added automatically

Change-Id: Ibceadc1d9f315044121e904f97e53aafec3b7cfa

commit_message:
Remove Python 2.6 classifier

We have decided to remove Python 2.6 support, this commit
removes Python 2.6 classifier before dropping any Python
2.6 support in code.

Change-Id: I2e29e13a747e66a984186af9ec53ab23cfc150f3

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables
* Remove requirements.txt from deps, as this is
  already added automatically


Change-Id: I12435cf9688866a78b368c17ef5cfb9fcae86a79

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables
* Remove requirements.txt from deps, as this is
  already added automatically

Change-Id: Iaeec42e9cf4fb01841e048f265f44772b6615050

commit_message:
Add new crumb-style menu.

Adds a new crumb-style menu, providing a link to the previously
hidden tests page, and presenting hierarchical navigation to users.
A new directive is added which can be placed within page headers
to create a breadcrumb menu to which pages can add their own
additional entries.

Change-Id: I1d31ee98f7c9fe27e6bd610adc6f4bce8097d5b6

Remove Python 2.6 classifier

We have decided to remove Python 2.6 support, this commit
removes Python 2.6 classifier before dropping any Python
2.6 support in code.

> Using oslo-config-generator against a modified version of Tempest, 
> I was not able to generate group help [...]

Could you provide me those changes?

> My original code had a serious bug that needed deeper architectural
> changes, which is why I abandoned it

Could you explain this to me please? I don't have enough knowledge
of the "oslo.config" project.

> in debugging against the group lookup every group is auto-created 
> at configuration lookup time.

I thought the autocreation of the group happens only once?! I'm not
sure what I'm doing wrong. 

Thanks for your review!

W-1 until this is clarified.'}, {'account_id': 7822, 'date': '2015-11-09 17:28:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

That it works with nova is great information. In looking at the serialproxy code, the reason the help text is generated is because the options are registered with the config object. In some projects, like Tempest, this is not the case. I see two possible solutions to the problem:

1- Require projects to register groups with the conf object. This may be against the design principles of oslo.config, since they already provide a discovery mechanism that does not rely on registration.

2- Add a new discovery method, list_opt_groups(), that provides tuples of the group names and objects that can be used to look up the group information. The projects can optionally define list_opt_groups() if they want to provide group help information without breaking existing projects.

Either choice would require an update to documentation and announcement to the dev mailing list.'}, {'account_id': 11303, 'date': '2015-11-09 18:14:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-06 13:08:28.000000000', 'message': 'Add help text generation for OptGroups

The OptGroup help text can now be generated.

Closed Bug: #1395819

(Co-)Author: Chris Hoge <chris@hogepodge.com>
Cherry-picked from commit c99822795c5c97864492ad04c77c6b79801c1e1f
and slightly changed.
Change-Id: I3cbdaa7e5dfb75d4c9eb687e68d3a35e61550d1b
'}, {'created': '2015-11-10 13:09:01.000000000', 'message': 'Add help text generation for OptGroups

The OptGroup help text can now be generated. The precondition is
that the OptGroup objects get provided in the "list_opts" interface.
Because OptGroup objects are not sortable, we use their name for the

commit_message:
Add help text generation for OptGroups

The OptGroup help text can now be generated. The precondition is
that the OptGroup objects get provided in the "list_opts" interface.
Because OptGroup objects are not sortable, we use their name for the
sorting. This allows also to provide a mixture of OptGroup objects and
OptGroup names for "list_opts".

Closed Bug: #1395819

(Co-)Author: Chris Hoge <chris@openstack.org>
Cherry-picked from commit c99822795c5c97864492ad04c77c6b79801c1e1f
and slightly changed.
Change-Id: I3cbdaa7e5dfb75d4c9eb687e68d3a35e61550d1b

commit_message:
cleanup tox.ini

* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables

Change-Id: Idb0a475054743fa716c7948e974a7268862c74c7

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables


Change-Id: I4c7772674eec553a131bb31396fb2742d505d452

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables
* Remove requirements.txt from deps, as this is
  already added automatically

Change-Id: I0441d771f554c86f3069bf62999c41f9b3ced99d

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Fix clickjacking attack vulnerability in nginx

For Fuel web interface and other sites served by nginx on fuel master
we should use X-Frame-Options SAMEORIGIN to prevent from clickjacking,
e.g. the page can only be displayed in a frame on the same
origin as the page itself.

Change-Id: Ie8d6e4e92222ac9bb7c489dd0a5aff833fabe873
Closes-Bug: #1497194

commit_message:
Improved integration module documentation

. Updated example to define DOMAIN and get_available_languages()
  as seen in several projects.
. Ensured myapp is consistent in various examples.
. Emphasized note on private naming implementation.
. Updated example to show get_available_languages().

Change-Id: I2f925a7631677aa0534de668a617458febf0bb08

commit_message:
[Ironic] Add baremetal network for ironic

This change adds:
* new optional baremetal network
* baremetal sections in Neutron L3 configuration

Ironic requires separate baremetal network on infra nodes and neutron flat
network mapped to this physical network.

New baremetal network is optional and depends on Ironic component enabled in
settings.

Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic (partially)
Change-Id: I742bf69d3f3ac5e4b4ecd39a12e3171c566563e8

commit_message:
Substitute copypasted natural sorting algorithm with a library

"javascript-natural-sort" NPM package provides the same
algorithm, but in a form of a reusable library.

Change-Id: Ie3f18bc87a66d25be28f18ce81701f1720231a41

commit_message:
Fix mock nbd block devices

NBD client creates a number of empty devices like /dev/nbd0..15
To fix the issue, before processing a partition script checks if
that partition was present in lsblk output.

Change-Id: I118c36a78e4661f82d4c11209ca98dca0fb2716a
Closes-Bug: #1510851

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 and cleanup tox.ini

* Remove support for python 2.6
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables
* Remove requirements.txt from deps, as this is
  already added automatically

Change-Id: I4f650eaa07624b889a52570e628a21e905f2bd46

commit_message:
Enabling DeprecationWarning if session is not provided

DeprecationWarning is ignored by default. Enable it so
that the deprecation message is displayed.

Change-Id: I40bfc82555d757eaba237b638bcd2753417f14f6
Closes-bug: #1515967

The OpenStack Ansible project is embarking on moving the various roles within our project into separate repositories to enable the use of the greater ansible galaxy deployment pattern (which is an Ansible best practice) and has been asked for repeatedly in the community to enable others to consume the work that we've done as standalone resources. Additionally, the changes being worked on within the project follow prior art from Chef and Puppet where the chef-cookbooks and puppet-modules have been broken out into separate repositories. Being that none of these repositories are related in behavior and that we're looking to be more deployer friendly / Ansible-centric I don't think lessons learned in Murano apply here."}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-11-11 17:33:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-11 19:03:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

commit_message:
Added new projects for the OSA role break out

The change adds new projects for the roles within OpenStack-Ansible
This is the first batch for the break out work which encompases the
OpenStack-Ansible play `setup-hosts.yml`.

New projects:
    - openstack-ansible-security
    - openstack-ansible-specs
    - openstack-ansible-lxc_container_create
    - openstack-ansible-lxc_hosts
    - openstack-ansible-py_from_git
    - openstack-ansible-openstack_hosts
    - openstack-ansible-pip_install
    - openstack-ansible-rsyslog_client
    - openstack-ansible-apt_package_pinning

The related review for the governance repository is
https://review.openstack.org/244166

Implements: blueprint independent-role-repositories
Change-Id: Ibfd5e745b7c5836b1c421b06ff8ef1e122c14108
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Split do_build_image

Cut huge method with few new functions.
Not clear solution, but its allow us to avoid code duplication

Implements: blueprint dynamically-build-bootstrap
Related-Bug: #1444090

commit_message:
Block new connections in HAProxy netns for its reload time

And unblock after the reload operation finished.

This introduces a 1 second latency lag to new
TCP connections requests made in the middle of the
HAProxy reload operation (which takes normally ~20 ms).
Otherwise, those would likely be aborted with RST,
which is much worse than a 1 second lag.
Note, that the scope of the blocking rule is limited to the
HAProxy network namespace and doesn't affect other connections.

Closes-bug: #1510236

Change-Id: Ic33f7539421fd3a8306e72d2a0b1519d94263380
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
Co-author: Sergii Golovatiuk <sgolovatiuk@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fix return value for get_supervisor_pid

In bash, you cannot use return to return a string value so this change
fixes it so the get_supervisor_pid function echos the PID which is
captured where it is called to be checked.

Change-Id: I6fe71a977ca75d58cf87fef819ee8e74d6edfcdd
Closes-Bug: #1514798

commit_message:
cleanup tox.ini

* Remove skipsdist : Needs to be set only if 
  sdist is expensive
* Remove usedevelop : only needed when skipsdist 
  is set to True
* Remove install_command : We can just use the 
  default, we don't need to override
* Remove setenv : We can just use the default as
  we don't need any extra environment variables
* Remove requirements.txt from deps, as this is
  already added automatically

Change-Id: I334c8db354f212f3f990f3ba59f2aa46355dae74

Add install-guide Appendix for enabling PLUMgrid Plugin functionality
in openstack-ansible

Patch 3: Addressed Kevin's & Jesse's comments
         plumgrid clones outside of OSA
         neutron configs added to a new user file

Closes-Bug: #1516424

Signed-off-by: Javeria Khan <javeriak@plumgrid.com>

commit_message:
Rename manifest.yml to manifest.yaml

Yaml suggest to use .yaml when possible:
http://www.yaml.org/faq.html <http://www.yaml.org/faq.html>

This patch renames manifest.yml to manifest.yaml.

Change-Id: I5b0e648af594a67d14916d69bb4acc56512da647
Closes-Bug: #1487405

commit_message:
Lodgeit: Downgrade gate and check jobs to experimental

Enabling the pep8 and py27 gate/check jobs, before merging the
changes that fix the pep8 warnings and make the tests work, makes
Jenkins score Verified-2 on changes.

Downgrade the jobs to experimental.

Change-Id: I53935f50e0fadcb92a6b5472012515411f4cd933

commit_message:
avoid unnecessary inner join in get_resources() for SQL backend

To get distinct resource ids, we do a query on resource table which
inner join sample table, and apply filters on it.

Note that when sql_expire_samples_only is enabled, there will be
some resources without any sample, in such case we must use inner
join to avoid wrong result, no matter if there is a timestamp filter
or not.

But that option is disabled by default, so when there is no timestamp
filters, the inner join is unnecessary, we should avoid it to save
some RAM/CPU cost.

Change-Id: If85dbea15d42d42c6b0be7402c06f258e278b2eb
Closes-Bug: #1509677
(cherry picked from commit a4f442940551a8a38e26e132c7efa766226daa15)

commit_message:
Add nova.host constraint

Host aggregate map hosts with availability zone as a aggregate set.
We need this constraint to make sure correctness of all hosts.

blueprint support-host-aggregate

Change-Id: Ib9a265f17b30427b15b4a5a4febaa5c70e280462

commit_message:
Correct the conversion expression of unit_conversion transformer

The example in admin-guide-cloud doc about telemetry unit_conversion
transformer cannot work, because the conversion expression is wrong.

Change-Id: Id99669f094094cc2c0e0a7ebc72b764d68450e94
Closes-Bug: #1504955

commit_message:
Document release notes process

Since we added support for reno, document that submitters should
provide release notes with their changes. Rather then expecting
others to provide them at the end.

Change-Id: I021dab1a6e34eb0b46c0676b26c669013118c118

(1 comment)

Moving out template selection entirely to another template may be considered as a beautiful metaprogramming - by a couple of devs who could understand it a couple of months later :). Is it an established pattern within Django/ Horizon?

I'm still hesitating whether I should -1 it, so let my comment be a vote-less question for now."}, {'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-11-04 17:52:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

Timur,

I've used the pattern several times in Django, but I'm not sure how to answer whether it is an established pattern.  

Breaking the two into separate templates makes the two templates very easy to customize for anyone who needs to brand either experience.  If they live in a single template, people who just want to rebrand the login page, but not the modal login, will have to fork and maintain both use cases.

fwiw, they are simply just wrappers for the login form around a Bootstrap Panel vs. a Bootstrap Modal.

Will address Matthias' comments as soon as I can also."}, {'account_id': 8040, 'date': '2015-11-05 11:08:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: Code-Review+1

revisions: [{'created': '2015-09-02 21:13:40.000000000', 'message': "Horizon Login now inherits from Bootstrap Theme The Horizon login page was not properly inheriting its styles from its theme. The implementation was making use of the _modal_form.html template just to inherit a form, but there was no way to remove the modal classes with that implementation. Also, it makes it very difficult to easily override with a custom experience with so many layers of template extension. The login page should just use a standard Bootstrap 'panel' because this will inherit the look and feel of any theme very easily. Not all themes use box-shadow outside of a Modal; some chose to be very flat on purpose, and the built in panels will take advantage of this. The panel is a little bit wider than it was before, but it is now a standard Bootstrap column size, so its responsive down to a very small screen size. Improvements: * Logo is now an tag, which means it can automagically resize to fit in the available space * Unneccesary styles removed * _splash.scss was using in _login.html, which was confusing, so _splash.scss is renamed to _login.scss, and is now a class based style, so it can live in /components * Its now Theme ready and responsive Partially-Implements: blueprint horizon-theme-css-reorg Partially-Implements: blueprint bootstrap-html-standards Change-Id: Ie968414ab8ef2154623edfc21ce5623e8c4057c6 "}, {'created': '2015-09-03 04:14:06.000000000', 'message': "Horizon Login now inherits from Bootstrap Theme The Horizon login page was not properly inheriting its styles from its theme. Also, it makes it very difficult to easily override with a custom experience with so many layers of template extension. The login page should just use a standard Bootstrap 'panel' because this will inherit the look and feel of any theme very easily. commit_message: Horizon Login now inherits from Bootstrap Theme The Horizon login page was not properly inheriting its styles from its theme. The implementation was making use of the _modal_form.html template just to inherit a form, but there was no way to remove the modal classes with that implementation. The login page now uses a standard Bootstrap 'panel'. This will inherit the look and feel of any theme more naturally when its not inside of a modal, as not all themes use box-shadow outside of a modal; some chose to be very flat on purpose, and the built in panels take advantage of this. When used within the Region selector, it does need to exist within a modal, so some simple logic was added for the classes necessary. The panel is a little bit wider than it was before, but it is now a standard Bootstrap column size, so its responsive down to a very small screen size. The modal is a little bit wider than it was before as well, as it is is now the standard medium modal size for Bootstrap. Improvements: * Logo is now an tag, which means it can automagically resize to fit in the available space * Unneccesary styles removed * _splash.scss was only being used in _login.html, which was confusing, so _splash.scss is renamed to _login.scss, and is now a class based style, so it can live in /components * Its now Theme ready and responsive * Region Selector Login now has a proper modal backdrop * has-error help-text should not be alert alert-danger Partially-Implements: blueprint horizon-theme-css-reorg Partially-Implements: blueprint bootstrap-html-standards Change-Id: Ie968414ab8ef2154623edfc21ce5623e8c4057c6

commit_message:
Add transaction for setting agent_id in L3HARouterAgentPortBinding

To avoid having extra L3HARouterAgentPortBinding with l3_agent as
None, operation of setting l3_agent should be atomic.
For this purpose, transaction was added in methods
create_ha_port_and_bind and _bind_ha_router_to_agents.

Closes-Bug: #1499647

Change-Id: Iaad82fe522cfd70061daecf411c924fdc11b7e41

This is absolutely the Right Thing to do, and the implementation looks fine.

That said, it might be tidier to move this check out of update.py and into the Resource._needs_update() method. TemplateResource already overrides this method, so... less things to override ;)

It appears that would also fix a bug in convergence, which afaict is missing this resource type check altogether. It might be worth doing the move in a separate commit (with tests for convergence) and then making this change.

The only downside I can see is that this would change the behaviour of the update user hook. (It would now run where a resource type changes, whereas before it would not.) However: this is an extreme edge case, the new behaviour would actually be more consistent, and I can't imagine that anyone is relying on this."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-04 17:54:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

> That said, it might be tidier to move this check out of update.py and into the Resource._needs_update() method. 

Thanks for the feedback, I've given that a try, and it's not all that simple AFAICS - the problem is we only have the old/new ResourceDefinitions, not the actual new resource object, which makes determining if the new definition is a valid TemplateResource update quite hard.

The main problem is you have to attempt retrieving the new resource_type from the new ResourceDefinition, only that doesn't exist in the old stack environment (which is expected, because we're updating the old resource_type in-place.  This still seems to work out OK after the update completes though, as we switch over to the new stack & thus the new ResourceDefinition resource_type aligns with the new environment.

I'll keep poking at this, but I'm not quite sure how we resolve the transient mismatch in environment/type other than leaving the type comparison like I've implemented it here, or passing a reference to the actual new resource (similar to the prev_resource passed in with the old resource reference)"}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-04 18:44:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

To clarify my previous comment - it doesn't work because the new resource type doesn't exist in the current environment.

So I need to pass new_res into _needs_update like I'm doing already for can_update_in_place or it's impossible to derive the actual type of the new ResourceDefinition."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-11-04 22:00:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

On further reflection, this shouldn't actually be a special case at all. The bug applies to all kinds of changes. For example:

- You have e.g. an OS::Nova::Server resource. You want to rename the type of My::Custom::Type and map that to OS::Nova::Server in the environment. That should be allowed.

- You have an OS::Heat::SoftwareDeployments resource and you want to rename the type to OS::Heat::SoftwareDeploymentGroup (which is an alias for the same type). That should be allowed too - in fact, *needs* to be allowed if we ever want to remove the deprecated one.

I think the general rule "if the type string doesn't match, replace it" is wrong. It should be "if the type string maps to a different class, replace it". That would solve the TemplateResource case, and also do the right thing for every other case too.

In light of this and your comments above, I'm inclined to think that in update.py is still the right place for the check - it's not something that resource plugins should need/be able to override, and they don't have the data to do it correctly anyway. That won't fix convergence though, so I created bug 1513233 to track that case.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-05 17:04:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> if the type string maps to a different class, replace it

Isn't that what we do already with type(), e.g compare the before/after classes?

The problem is for TemplateResource, we don't see a template_resource.TemplateResource class:

2015-11-05 16:57:20.450 DEBUG heat.engine.update [-] SHDEBUG test1 type(new_res): <class 'heat.engine.resources.template_resource.My::TestResource2'> from (pid=7394) _process_new_resource_update /opt/stack/heat/heat/engine/update.py:139
2015-11-05 16:57:20.450 DEBUG heat.engine.update [-] SHDEBUG test1 type(existing_res): <class 'heat.engine.resources.template_resource.My::TestResource'> from (pid=7394) _process_new_resource_update /opt/stack/heat/heat/engine/update.py:143"}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-05 17:34:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Ok, for the benefit of anyone else following, the old comparison does new_res.type() which is not the same as the type(new_res) in my debug prints.

Neither approach works though, because TemplateResource subclasses TemplateResource since https://review.openstack.org/#/c/79291/3'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2015-11-06 01:47:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

We could just have a special case check for classes that extend TemplateResource'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-06 07:55:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> We could just have a special case check for classes that extend TemplateResource

Yeah, well that's what this patch basically already does, but if folks prefer I could just do the isinstance in update.py.

Zane had some ideas related to not subclassing TemplateResource for user provided resources (it was only added to support resource-type-show for resource_registry items from the global environment), which I'm still investigating, but for now I think two changes will suffice:

1. Switch from res.type() to type(res) in the update.py type comparison (this solves the alias issue zane mentioned, which is not addressed by this patch)

2. Special-case TemplateResource to check for subclasses and allow in-place update of all of them.

Will push another update later, but if folks have strong opinions on how we do (2) feel free to comment."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-06 10:45:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> I could just do the isinstance in update.py.

Actually no, I can't easily do that, because it introduces a import circular dependency, I remember now that's why I abstracted the test into the resource.Resource class and overrode it in TemplateResource."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-10 05:23:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Is it worth putting a note discouraging plugin authors from overriding, or have we given up on the idea of not subclassing TemplateResource on the fly?'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-11-11 23:34:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Allow in-place updates for all compatible types

We previously only allowed a resource to update in-place when the 'type'
field in the old and new templates matched. In an age of environment type
mappings, this is incorrect. Instead, allow a resource to be updated
in-place when the old and new resource plugins are of the same class, since
this is actually what determines whether handle_update is capable of
correctly updating the resource in-place.

There is a special-case for TemplateResource as we currently subclass it
for each template type, but all TemplateResource subclasses are in fact
capable of converting between each other via a stack update.

Change-Id: Iba4abf5efd9737ca6a17d8c91d5c54ab6d3f12e0
Co-Authored-By: Zane Bitter <zbitter@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1508115

infrastructure.

commit_message:
Add notification for service status change

Today external system cannot get notification based information about the nova
service status. Nova service status can be changed administratively via
via os-services/disable API.

Having such a notification helps to measure the length of maintenance windows
or indirectly notify users about maintenance actions that possibly effect the
operation of the infrastructure.

bp service-status-notification

Change-Id: Ib040cbb2917a99bc3164aa7efd09059f3318df1f

(4 comments)

I think this needs a lot more definition of what the actual notification bits look like.

We have already discussed (and I think agreed) that notifications should be objects, with versions, rules, etc. They self-serialize and have understandable semantics. This spec doesn't seem to propose we do that, but I think we should, especially since it seems nearly already agreed-upon.

I think that we could probably do what we want by having a top-level Notification object with well-defined metadata bits, and a payload field, which contains a PayloadObject. There can be a GenericPayloadObject which is merely a dict of unformatted strings, and more specific ones like InstancePayload, UsagePayload, etc.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 9708, 'date': '2015-09-28 15:17:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(4 comments)

Hi Dan, 

Thanks for the review.

I agree with the your comment that we need more details in this spec. I will try to add them but I need help and feedback to progress. This I why I published the spec in the current incomplete form.

The only reference about priory agreement I found is the etherpad [1] from the kilo summit. Do we have anything top of that?

I like the idea to have an object model for notifications. I will try to draft something based on your suggestions. However we have to provide some language agnostic description (e.g. JSON schema) of our notifications as well to the clients. I don't think we should duplicate the information so we either need to generate JSON schema from the object model or generate the object model from the JSON schema. What do you prefer?

Do you think this topic worth a nova design summit session in Tokyo?

I will continue working on this spec but any help is appreciated.

Cheers,
Gibi

[1] https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/kilo-crossproject-notifications"}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-09-30 00:39:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm a bit concerned of the rate of change of raw objects on the wire, especially as this is an externalized interface, and that's going to have to be documented at every step along the way.

Is there a reason we're not just using the REST representations of the data payloads (like Instance). It seems that matching representations on the front end and the back end would unify a lot of parsing code / logic, and versioning."}, {'account_id': 9708, 'date': '2015-10-27 13:12:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Hi Sean,

I tend to agree with that the rate of the change in case of the instance ovo might be a bit high. Between Kilo and Liberty there were 4 version bumps in the instance object with 2 + 0 + 4 + 10 added fields respectively. But I guess instance is the most frequently changing ovo in nova. Also these are additions only, so a robust parser that is compatible with instance version 1.19 (Kilo) does not need to be changed to provide the same level of information if it receives instance version 1.23 (Liberty) in the notification payload.
However I agree that using the REST representation might spare some code on the client side if the client already has the code to parse the REST responses.
Let's discuss this on Thursday on the half session dedicated to this spec. See: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/mitaka-nova-error-handling

Cheers,
Gibi"}, {'account_id': 9708, 'date': '2015-10-30 07:50:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 9708, 'date': '2015-10-30 07:50:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(5 comments)

Looking pretty solid.  I think we should explicitly state what is expected of a tools developer to utilize this feature.  I like using the object directly because as a developer of tools hanging off notifications it's really nice to get the full data model.

We're pretty much locking a tools developer into using python and importing nova modules so they can get the deserialization of the object, right?  

Also, we're making the assumption that re-hydrating an object from primitives will not attempt to load from the DB or otherwise do things that assume it's being called from inside a live nova system?  (Not sure if this is something that's done.)"}, {'account_id': 1865, 'date': '2015-11-04 09:40:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(4 comments)

Thanks for the very detailed specs. I have some questions, please have a look at my comments.
I do need to better understand all the notification system, at the moment it seems that the first alternative is a valid one, I do not have yet a strong opinion about it.'}, {'account_id': 9708, 'date': '2015-11-04 10:40:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(9 comments)

Guys, thanks for the comments. See my answers inline and see the new patch set.

Regarding the toolbox to consume notifications I think as a first step we simply provide a well defined payload and let the consumer decide how to consume it. Honestly consuming by importing nova code and re-hydrating the objects sounds complicated but it is not the only options. A consumer can build its own simplified object model based on (but not depending on) the nova object model (even in different languages). In a later spec we can propose to create a library to help python consumers, or we can generate json schemas from the nova object model that can be used to re-generate another object model on the consumer side (even in a different language). Brian, if you have some specific ideas I think it worth to put them in a subsequent spec to start discussing it with other consumers. What do you think?

Cheers,

[{'created': '2015-09-17 14:28:32.000000000', 'message': 'Versioned notification API

Notification interface of nova is not well defined and the current
notifications define a very inconsistent interface. There is no easy
way to see from the notification consumer point of view what is the format
and the content of the notification nova sends.

Nova developers can add new notifications to the system without specifying
the format and the content of the notification.

Moreover developers can change existing notifications without considering
backward compatibility towards the notification consumers.

Due to this situation maintaining a consumer for nova notifications is really
hard.

commit_message:
Versioned notification API

The notification interface of nova is not well defined and the current
notifications define a very inconsistent interface. There is no easy
way to see from the notification consumer point of view what is the format
and the content of the notification nova sends.

Implements: blueprint versioned-notification-api
Change-Id: Ieda738ffabdb8f826865052dd01a3ecb8dfe20dd

commit_message:
Make identity_client use **kwargs

As we discussed on
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/068864.html
All http POST/PUT methods need to contain **kwargs as their arguments.
This patch makes identity_client use **kwargs.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I65cd07d4263d42e858f17a307e74cf9735cdf7f9

commit_message:
Fix race condition for /openstack directories

To resolve a possible race condition when containers are creating
log directories the /openstack directory and its basic sub-directories
are being created within the openstack_hosts role which will ensure that
the appropriate skeleton is available when the containers go to build
in subsequent tasks.

Closes-bug: #1426254
Change-Id: Icdbddf285f8b898518657b082a9263a2923c97c4
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit de6f3a21e04daff5ea583653bef6ed62de624635)

commit_message:
Sync with oslo-incubator

As noted in the email below, the oslo-incubator code is going away.
This is expected to be a last sync from that repo. We will need to
figure out how this code should be maintained in our repo later.

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/079343.html

commit_message:
devstack: Use midonet stable/v2015.06.2 by default

v1 support has been removed from midonet master.
stable/v2015.06.2 is the last stable branch with v1 support.

This change goes to stable/kilo directly because it isn't
appropriate for master.  For master, we are going to make
v2 (aka ZOOM) the default. [1]

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/220705/

Closes-Bug: #1482080
Change-Id: I472aa3392f3265e2d047cbc5391f380ea649c0f0

messages:
